# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electronics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In electronics, an **analog-to-digital converter** (**ADC**, **A/D**, or **A-to-D**) is a system that converts an analog signal, such as from fingers touching a touchscreen, sound entering a microphone, or light entering a digital camera, into a digital signal.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] An ADC may also provide an isolated measurement, such as an electronic device that converts an analog input voltage or current to a digital number representing the magnitude of the voltage or current.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Typically, the digital output is a two's complement binary number that is proportional to the input, but there are other possibilities.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Due to the complexity and the need for precisely matched components, all but the most specialized ADCs are implemented as integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] These typically take the form of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) mixed-signal integrated circuit chips that integrate both analog and digital circuits.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A digital-to-analog converter (DAC) performs the reverse function; it converts a digital signal into an analog signal.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] An ADC converts a continuous-time and continuous-amplitude analog signal to a discrete-time and discrete-amplitude digital signal.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The conversion involves quantization of the input, so it necessarily introduces a small amount of quantization error.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Furthermore, instead of continuously performing the conversion, an ADC does the conversion periodically, sampling the input, and limiting the allowable bandwidth of the input signal.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The performance of an ADC is primarily characterized by its bandwidth, dynamic range and signal-to-noise and distortion ratio (SNDR).
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The bandwidth of an ADC is set largely by its sampling rate.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The SNDR is influenced by many factors, including the resolution, noise floor, linearity and accuracy (how well the quantization levels match the true analog signal).
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Aliasing and jitter will degrade these specifications.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The SNDR of an ADC is often summarized in terms of its effective number of bits (ENOB), the number of bits of each measure it returns that are, on average, not noise.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] An ideal ADC has an ENOB equal to its resolution.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] If an ADC operates at a sampling rate greater than twice the bandwidth of the signal, then per the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, near-perfect reconstruction is possible.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The presence of quantization error limits the SNDR of even an ideal ADC.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] When the SNDR of the ADC exceeds that of the input signal, the effects of quantization error may be neglected, resulting in an essentially perfect digital representation of the bandlimited analog input signal.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The resolution of the converter indicates the number of different, i.e., discrete, values it can produce over the allowed range of analog input values.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Thus, a particular resolution determines the magnitude of the quantization error and therefore determines the maximum possible signal-to-noise ratio for an ideal ADC without the use of oversampling.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The input samples are usually stored electronically in binary form within the ADC, so the resolution is usually expressed in bits.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Resolution can also be defined electrically, and expressed in volts.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The change in voltage required to guarantee a change in the output code level is called the least significant bit (LSB) voltage.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The resolution *Q* of the ADC is equal to the LSB voltage.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] where *M* is the ADC's resolution in bits and *E*FSR is the full-scale voltage range (also called 'span').
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] where *V*RefHi and *V*RefLow are the upper and lower extremes, respectively, of the voltages that can be coded.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] where *M* is the ADC's resolution in bits.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] That is, one voltage interval is assigned in between two consecutive code levels.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In many cases, the useful resolution of a converter is limited by the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) and other errors in the overall system expressed as an ENOB.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization error is introduced by the quantization inherent in an ideal ADC.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] It is a rounding error between the analog input voltage to the ADC and the output digitized value.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The error is nonlinear and signal-dependent.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] where M is the number of quantization bits.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] For example, for a 16-bit ADC, the quantization error is 96.3 dB below the maximum level.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization error is distributed from DC to the Nyquist frequency.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Consequently, if part of the ADC's bandwidth is not used, as is the case with oversampling, some of the quantization error will occur out-of-band, effectively improving the SQNR for the bandwidth in use.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In an oversampled system, noise shaping can be used to further increase SQNR by forcing more quantization error out of band.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In ADCs, performance can usually be improved using dither.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] This is a very small amount of random noise (e.g., white noise), which is added to the input before conversion.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Its effect is to randomize the state of the LSB based on the signal.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Rather than the signal simply getting cut off altogether at low levels, it extends the effective range of signals that the ADC can convert, at the expense of a slight increase in noise.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Dither can only increase the resolution of a sampler.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] It cannot improve the linearity, and thus, accuracy does not necessarily improve.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization distortion in an audio signal of very low level with respect to the bit depth of the ADC is correlated with the signal and sounds distorted and unpleasant.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] With dithering, the distortion is transformed into noise.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The undistorted signal may be recovered accurately by averaging over time.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Dithering is also used in integrating systems such as electricity meters.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Since the values are added together, the dithering produces results that are more exact than the LSB of the analog-to-digital converter.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Dither is often applied when quantizing photographic images to a fewer number of bits per pixel—the image becomes noisier but to the eye looks far more realistic than the quantized image, which otherwise becomes banded.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] This analogous process may help to visualize the effect of dither on an analog audio signal that is converted to digital.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization error and (assuming the ADC is intended to be linear) non-linearity are intrinsic to any analog-to-digital conversion.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] These errors are measured in a unit called the least significant bit (LSB).
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In the above example of an 8-bit ADC, an error of one LSB is 1⁄256 of the full signal range, or about 0.4%.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] All ADCs suffer from nonlinearity errors caused by their physical imperfections, causing their output to deviate from a linear function (or some other function, in the case of a deliberately nonlinear ADC) of their input.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] These errors can sometimes be mitigated by calibration, or prevented by testing.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Important parameters for linearity are integral nonlinearity and differential nonlinearity.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] These nonlinearities introduce distortion that can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio performance of the ADC and thus reduce its effective resolution.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] When digitizing a sine wave $x(t)=A\sin {(2\pi f_{0}t)}$ , the use of a non-ideal sampling clock will result in some uncertainty in when samples are recorded.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Provided that the actual sampling time uncertainty due to clock jitter is $\Delta t$ , the error caused by this phenomenon can be estimated as $E_{ap}\leq |x'(t)\Delta t|\leq 2A\pi f_{0}\Delta t$ .
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] This will result in additional recorded noise that will reduce the effective number of bits (ENOB) below that predicted by quantization error alone.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The error is zero for DC, small at low frequencies, but significant with signals of high amplitude and high frequency.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The effect of jitter on performance can be compared to quantization error: $\Delta t<{\frac {1}{2^{q}\pi f_{0}}}$ , where q is the number of ADC bits.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The resolution of ADCs with a digitization bandwidth between 1 MHz and 1 GHz is limited by jitter.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] For lower bandwidth conversions such as when sampling audio signals at 44.1 kHz, clock jitter has a less significant impact on performance.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] An analog signal is continuous in time and it is necessary to convert this to a flow of digital values.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] It is therefore required to define the rate at which new digital values are sampled from the analog signal.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The rate of new values is called the *sampling rate* or *sampling frequency* of the converter.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A continuously varying bandlimited signal can be sampled and then the original signal can be reproduced from the discrete-time values by a reconstruction filter.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem implies that a faithful reproduction of the original signal is only possible if the sampling rate is higher than twice the highest frequency of the signal.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Since a practical ADC cannot make an instantaneous conversion, the input value must necessarily be held constant during the time that the converter performs a conversion (called the *conversion time*).
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] An input circuit called a sample and hold performs this task—in most cases by using a capacitor to store the analog voltage at the input, and using an electronic switch or gate to disconnect the capacitor from the input.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Many ADC integrated circuits include the sample and hold subsystem internally.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] An ADC works by sampling the value of the input at discrete intervals in time.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Provided that the input is sampled above the Nyquist rate, defined as twice the highest frequency of interest, then all frequencies in the signal can be reconstructed.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] If frequencies above half the Nyquist rate are sampled, they are incorrectly detected as lower frequencies, a process referred to as aliasing.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Aliasing occurs because instantaneously sampling a function at two or fewer times per cycle results in missed cycles, and therefore, the appearance of an incorrectly lower frequency.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] For example, a 2 kHz sine wave being sampled at 1.5 kHz would be reconstructed as a 500 Hz sine wave.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] To avoid aliasing, the input to an ADC must be low-pass filtered to remove frequencies above half the sampling rate.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] This filter is called an *anti-aliasing filter*, and is essential for a practical ADC system that is applied to analog signals with higher frequency content.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In applications where protection against aliasing is essential, oversampling may be used to greatly reduce or even eliminate it.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Although aliasing in most systems is unwanted, it can be exploited to provide simultaneous down-mixing of a band-limited high-frequency signal (see undersampling and frequency mixer).
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The alias is effectively the lower heterodyne of the signal frequency and sampling frequency.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] For economy, signals are often sampled at the minimum rate required, with the result that the quantization error introduced is white noise spread over the whole passband of the converter.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Oversampling is typically used in audio frequency ADCs where the required sampling rate (typically 44.1 or 48 kHz) is very low compared to the clock speed of typical transistor circuits (>1 MHz).
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In this case, the performance of the ADC can be greatly increased at little or no cost.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Furthermore, as any aliased signals are also typically out of band, aliasing can often be eliminated using very low-cost filters.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The sliding scale method was introduced in 1963 by Cottini, Gatti, and Svelto as a way to reduce differential nonlinearity in analog-to-digital converters used in radiation detection systems.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In those applications, the digital output codes of an ADC are accumulated into histograms representing measured particle energies.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] If some output codes correspond to slightly wider or narrower input voltage ranges than others, the resulting *bins* in the histogram are uneven.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] This produces visible structure in what should otherwise be smooth spectra.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The method works by adding a known random analog offset to the input before conversion and subtracting the corresponding digital value afterward.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Although the final numerical result is unchanged, each conversion effectively occurs at a different position along the ADC transfer characteristic.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] When many samples are accumulated, the output codes represent an average over several adjacent code widths, reducing the impact of differential nonlinearity.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] There are several common ways of implementing an electronic ADC.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Resistor-capacitor (RC) circuits have a known voltage charging and discharging curve that can be used to solve for an unknown analog value.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The Wilkinson ADC is a type of linear ramp converter, originally described by Denys Wilkinson in 1950.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In this architecture, the input pulse is compared with a linearly voltage ramp generated by charging a capacitor with a constant current source.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A comparator produces a gate signal that remains active until the ramp reaches the amplitude of the input pulse.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The duration of this gate interval is therefore proportional to the input amplitude.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] During this interval, pulses from a constant-frequency clock are counted by a register, and the final count represents the digital output.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Because the ramp can be generated with high precision, the output codes are contiguous and nearly uniform in width, giving the converter good differential linearity.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The conversion time is proportional to the input amplitude and inversely proportional to the clock frequency, so larger signals require longer conversion times.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Wilkinson converters were widely used in multichannel analyzers for nuclear spectroscopy through the 1960s and 1970s due to their linearity and suitability for histogram-based measurements.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] and solving for the unknown resistance or capacitance using those starting and ending datapoints.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] This is similar but contrasts with the Wilkinson ADC, which measures an unknown voltage with a known resistance and capacitance, by instead measuring an unknown resistance or capacitance with a known voltage.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] For example, the positive (and/or negative) pulse width from a 555 Timer IC in monostable or astable mode represents the time it takes to charge (and/or discharge) its capacitor from 1⁄3 *V*supply to 2⁄3 *V*supply.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] By sending this pulse into a microcontroller with an accurate clock, the duration of the pulse can be measured and converted using the capacitor charging equation to produce the value of the unknown resistance or capacitance.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Larger resistances and capacitances will take a longer time to measure than smaller ones.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] And the accuracy is limited by the accuracy of the microcontroller clock and the amount of time available to measure the value, which potentially might even change during measurement or be affected by external parasitics.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A flash ADC, also known as a parallel search ADC, employs a bank of voltage comparators sampling the input signal in parallel, each with a different voltage threshold.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The circuit consists of a resistive divider network, a set of voltage comparators and a priority encoder.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Each node of the resistive divider provides a voltage threshold for one comparator.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The comparator outputs are applied to a priority encoder, which generates a binary number proportional to the input voltage.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Flash ADCs have a large die size and high power dissipation.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] They are used in a variety of applications, including video, wideband communications, and for digitizing other fast signals.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The circuit has the advantage of high speed as the conversion takes place simultaneously rather than sequentially.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Typical conversion time is 100 ns or less.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Conversion time is limited only by the speed of the comparator and of the priority encoder.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] This type of ADC has the disadvantage that for each additional output bit, the number of comparators required almost doubles, and the priority encoder becomes more complex.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A successive-approximation ADC uses a comparator and a binary search to successively narrow a range that contains the input voltage.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] At each successive step, the converter compares the input voltage to the output of an internal digital-to-analog converter (DAC), which initially represents the midpoint of the allowed input voltage range.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] At each step in this process, the approximation is stored in a successive approximation register (SAR) and the output of the digital-to-analog converter is updated for a comparison over a narrower range.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A ramp-compare ADC produces a saw-tooth signal that ramps up or down, then quickly returns to zero.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] When the ramp starts, a timer starts counting.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] When the ramp voltage matches the input, a comparator fires, and the timer's value is recorded.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Timed ramp converters can be implemented economically, however, the ramp time may be sensitive to temperature because the circuit generating the ramp is often a simple analog integrator.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A more accurate converter uses a clocked counter driving a DAC.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A special advantage of the ramp-compare system is that converting a second signal just requires another comparator and another register to store the timer value.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] To reduce sensitivity to input changes during conversion, a sample and hold can charge a capacitor with the instantaneous input voltage and the converter can time the time required to discharge with a constant current.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] An **integrating ADC** (also **dual-slope** or **multi-slope** ADC) applies the unknown input voltage to the input of an integrator and allows the voltage to ramp for a fixed time period (the run-up period).
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Then a known reference voltage of opposite polarity is applied to the integrator and is allowed to ramp until the integrator output returns to zero (the run-down period).
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The input voltage is computed as a function of the reference voltage, the constant run-up time period, and the measured run-down time period.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The run-down time measurement is usually made in units of the converter's clock, so longer integration times allow for higher resolutions.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Likewise, the speed of the converter can be improved by sacrificing resolution.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Converters of this type (or variations on the concept) are used in most digital voltmeters for their linearity and flexibility.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] This frequency is then measured by a counter and converted to an output code proportional to the analog input.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The main advantage of these converters is that it is possible to transmit frequency even in a noisy environment or in isolated form.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] However, the limitation of this circuit is that the output of the voltage-to-frequency converter depends upon an RC product whose value cannot be accurately maintained over temperature and time.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The analog part of the circuit consists of a high input impedance buffer, precision integrator and a voltage comparator.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The converter first integrates the analog input signal for a fixed duration and then it integrates an internal reference voltage of opposite polarity until the integrator output is zero.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The main disadvantage of this circuit is the long duration time.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A *delta-encoded* or *counter-ramp* ADC has an up-down counter that feeds a DAC.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The input signal and the DAC both go to a comparator.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The circuit uses negative feedback from the comparator to adjust the counter until the DAC's output matches the input signal and number is read from the counter.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Delta converters have very wide ranges and high resolution, but the conversion time is dependent on the input signal behavior, though it will always have a guaranteed worst-case.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Delta converters are often very good choices to read real-world signals as most signals from physical systems do not change abruptly.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Some converters combine the delta and successive approximation approaches; this works especially well when high-frequency components of the input signal are known to be small in magnitude.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A *pipelined ADC* (also called *subranging quantizer*) uses two or more conversion steps.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In a second step, the difference to the input signal is determined with a DAC.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] This difference is then converted more precisely, and the results are combined in the last step.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] This can be considered a refinement of the successive-approximation ADC wherein the feedback reference signal consists of the interim conversion of a whole range of bits (for example, four bits) rather than just the next-most-significant bit.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] By combining the merits of the successive approximation and flash ADCs this type is fast, has a high resolution, and can be implemented efficiently.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A **delta-sigma ADC** (also known as a **sigma-delta ADC**) is based on a negative feedback loop with an analog filter and low resolution (often 1 bit) but high sampling rate ADC and DAC.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The feedback loop continuously corrects accumulated quantization errors and performs noise shaping: quantization noise is reduced in the low frequencies of interest, but is increased in higher frequencies.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Those higher frequencies may then be removed by a downsampling digital filter, which also converts the data stream from that high sampling rate with low bit depth to a lower rate with higher bit depth.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A time-interleaved ADC uses M parallel ADCs where each ADC samples data every M:th cycle of the effective sample clock.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The result is that the sample rate is increased M times compared to what each individual ADC can manage.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In practice, the individual differences between the M ADCs degrade the overall performance reducing the spurious-free dynamic range (SFDR).
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] However, techniques exist to correct for these time-interleaving mismatch errors.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Longer integration times allow for higher resolutions.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The two parts of the ADC may be widely separated, with the frequency signal passed through an opto-isolator or transmitted wirelessly.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Some such ADCs use sine wave or square wave frequency modulation; others use pulse-frequency modulation.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Such ADCs were once the most popular way to show a digital display of the status of a remote analog sensor.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] A time-stretch analog-to-digital converter (TS-ADC) digitizes a very wide bandwidth analog signal, that cannot be digitized by a conventional electronic ADC, by time-stretching the signal prior to digitization.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] It commonly uses a photonic preprocessor to time-stretch the signal, which effectively slows the signal down in time and compresses its bandwidth.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] As a result, an electronic ADC, that would have been too slow to capture the original signal, can now capture this slowed-down signal.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] For continuous capture of the signal, the front end also divides the signal into multiple segments in addition to time-stretching.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Each segment is individually digitized by a separate electronic ADC.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Finally, a digital signal processor rearranges the samples and removes any distortions added by the preprocessor to yield the binary data that is the digital representation of the original analog signal.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] In many cases, the most expensive part of an integrated circuit is the pins, because they make the package larger, and each pin has to be connected to the integrated circuit's silicon.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] To save pins, it is common for ADCs to send their data one bit at a time over a serial interface to the computer, with each bit coming out when a clock signal changes state.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] This saves quite a few pins on the ADC package, and in many cases, does not make the overall design any more complex.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Commercial ADCs often have several inputs that feed the same converter, usually through an analog multiplexer.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Different models of ADC may include sample and hold circuits, instrumentation amplifiers or differential inputs, where the quantity measured is the difference between two inputs.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Soundstream was probably the first digital audio recording system of commercial importance.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Analog-to-digital converters are integral to modern music reproduction technology and digital audio workstation-based sound recording.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Music may be produced on computers using an analog recording and therefore analog-to-digital converters are needed to create the pulse-code modulation (PCM) data streams that go onto compact discs and digital music files.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] The current crop of analog-to-digital converters utilized in music can sample at rates up to 192 kilohertz.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Many recording studios record in 24-bit 96 kHz pulse-code modulation (PCM) format and then downsample and dither the signal for Compact Disc Digital Audio production (44.1 kHz) or to 48 kHz for radio and television broadcast applications.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] ADCs are required in digital signal processing systems that process, store, or transport virtually any analog signal in digital form.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] TV tuner cards, for example, use fast video analog-to-digital converters.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Slow on-chip 8-, 10-, 12-, or 16-bit analog-to-digital converters are common in microcontrollers.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Digital storage oscilloscopes need very fast analog-to-digital converters, also crucial for software-defined radio and their new applications.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Digital imaging systems commonly use analog-to-digital converters for digitizing pixels.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Some radar systems use analog-to-digital converters to convert signal strength to digital values for subsequent signal processing.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Many other in situ and remote sensing systems commonly use analogous technology.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Many sensors in scientific instruments produce an analog signal; temperature, pressure, pH, light intensity etc.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] All these signals can be amplified and fed to an ADC to produce a digital representation.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Flat-panel displays are inherently digital and need an ADC to process an analog signal such as composite or VGA.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Testing an analog-to-digital converter requires an analog input source and hardware to send control signals and capture digital data output.
[src:electronics/analog-to-digital-converter] Some ADCs also require an accurate source of reference signal.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] A **capacitor** is a device that stores electrical energy by accumulating electric charges on two closely spaced surfaces that are insulated from each other.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] It is a passive electronic component with two terminals.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] A capacitor was originally known as a **condenser**, a term still encountered in a few compound names, such as the *condenser microphone*.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Colloquially, a capacitor may be called a ***cap***.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The utility of a capacitor depends on its capacitance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] While some capacitance exists between any two electrical conductors in proximity in a circuit, a capacitor is a component designed specifically to add capacitance to some part of the circuit.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The physical form and construction of practical capacitors vary widely and many types of capacitor are in common use.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Most capacitors contain at least two electrical conductors, often in the form of metallic plates or surfaces separated by a dielectric medium.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] A conductor may be a foil, thin film, sintered bead of metal, or an electrolyte.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The nonconducting dielectric acts to increase the capacitor's charge capacity.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Materials commonly used as dielectrics include glass, ceramic, plastic film, paper, mica, air, and oxide layers.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] No current actually flows through a perfect dielectric.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] However, there is a flow of charge through the source circuit.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] If the condition is maintained sufficiently long, the current through the source circuit ceases.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] If a time-varying voltage is applied across the leads of the capacitor, the source experiences an ongoing current due to the charging and discharging cycles of the capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are widely used as parts of electrical circuits in many common electrical devices.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Unlike a resistor, an ideal capacitor does not dissipate energy, although real-life capacitors do dissipate a small amount .
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The earliest forms of capacitors were created in the 1740s, when European experimenters discovered that electric charge could be stored in water-filled glass jars that came to be known as Leyden jars.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Today, capacitors are widely used in electronic circuits for blocking direct current while allowing alternating current to pass.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In analog filter networks, they smooth the output of power supplies.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In resonant circuits they tune radios to particular frequencies.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In electric power transmission systems, they stabilize voltage and power flow.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The property of energy storage in capacitors was exploited as dynamic memory in early digital computers, and still is in modern DRAM.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The most common example of natural capacitance are the static charges accumulated between clouds in the sky and the surface of the Earth, where the air between them serves as the dielectric.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] This results in bolts of lightning when the breakdown voltage of the air is exceeded.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In October 1745, Ewald Georg von Kleist of Pomerania, Germany, found that charge could be stored by connecting a high-voltage electrostatic generator by a wire to a volume of water in a hand-held glass jar.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist's hand and the water acted as conductors and the jar as a dielectric (although details of the mechanism were incorrectly identified at the time).
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist found that touching the wire resulted in a powerful spark, much more painful than that obtained from an electrostatic machine.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The following year, the Dutch physicist Pieter van Musschenbroek invented a similar capacitor, which was named the Leyden jar, after the University of Leiden where he worked.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Daniel Gralath was the first to combine several jars in parallel to increase the charge storage capacity.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Benjamin Franklin investigated the Leyden jar and came to the conclusion that the charge was stored on the glass, not in the water as others had assumed.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] He also adopted the term "battery", (denoting the increase of power with a row of similar units as in a battery of cannon), subsequently applied to clusters of electrochemical cells.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In 1747, Leyden jars were made by coating the inside and outside of jars with metal foil, leaving a space at the mouth to prevent arcing between the foils.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The earliest unit of capacitance was the jar, equivalent to about 1.11 nanofarads.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] More compact construction methods began to be used, such as a flexible dielectric sheet (like oiled paper) sandwiched between sheets of metal foil, rolled or folded into a small package.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Early capacitors were known as *condensers*, a term that is still occasionally used today, particularly in high power applications, such as automotive systems.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The term became deprecated because of the ambiguous meaning of steam condenser, with *capacitor* being recommended by the British Engineering Standards Association in 1926, although it took several decades for the term to predominate.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Since the beginning of the study of electricity, non-conductive materials like glass, porcelain, paper and mica have been used as insulators.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Decades later, these materials were also well-suited for use as the dielectric for the first capacitors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Paper capacitors, made by sandwiching a strip of impregnated paper between strips of metal and rolling the result into a cylinder, were commonly used in the late 19th century; their manufacture started in 1876, and they were used from the early 20th century as decoupling capacitors in telephony.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Porcelain was used in the first ceramic capacitors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In the early years of Marconi's wireless transmitting apparatus, porcelain capacitors were used for high voltage and high frequency application in the transmitters.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] On the receiver side, smaller mica capacitors were used for resonant circuits.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Mica capacitors were invented in 1909 by William Dubilier.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Prior to World War II, mica was the most common dielectric for capacitors in the United States.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Charles Pollak (born Karol Pollak), the inventor of the first electrolytic capacitors, found out that the oxide layer on an aluminum anode remained stable in a neutral or alkaline electrolyte, even when the power was switched off.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] 672,913 for an "Electric liquid capacitor with aluminum electrodes".
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Solid electrolyte tantalum capacitors were invented by Bell Laboratories in the early 1950s as a miniaturized and more reliable low-voltage support capacitor to complement their newly invented transistor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] With the development of plastic materials by organic chemists during the Second World War, the capacitor industry began to replace paper with thinner polymer films.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] One very early development in film capacitors was described in British Patent 587,953 in 1944.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Electric double-layer capacitors (now supercapacitors) were invented in 1957 when H.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Becker developed a "Low voltage electrolytic capacitor with porous carbon electrodes".
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] He believed that the energy was stored as a charge in the carbon pores used in his capacitor as in the pores of the etched foils of electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The MOS capacitor was later widely adopted as a storage capacitor in memory chips, and as the basic building block of the charge-coupled device (CCD) in image sensor technology.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Robert Dennard invented modern DRAM architecture, combining a single MOS transistor per capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] A capacitor consists of two conductors separated by a non-conductive region.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The non-conductive region can either be a vacuum or an electrical insulator material known as a dielectric.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Examples of dielectric media are glass, air, paper, plastic, ceramic, and even a semiconductor depletion region chemically identical to the conductors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] From Coulomb's law, a charge on one conductor will exert a force on the charge carriers within the other conductor, attracting opposite polarity charge and repelling like polarity charges, thus an opposite polarity charge will be induced on the surface of the other conductor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The conductors thus hold equal and opposite charges on their facing surfaces, and the dielectric develops an electric field.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] A capacitance of one farad (1 F) means that one coulomb of charge on each conductor causes a voltage of one volt across the device.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Because the conductors (or plates) are close together, the opposite charges on the conductors attract one another due to their electric fields, allowing the capacitor to store more charge for a given voltage than when the conductors are separated, yielding a larger capacitance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In practical devices, charge build-up sometimes affects the capacitor mechanically, causing its capacitance to vary.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In the hydraulic analogy, voltage is analogous to water pressure and electrical current through a wire is analogous to water flow through a pipe.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] A capacitor is like an elastic diaphragm within the pipe.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Although water cannot pass through the diaphragm, it moves as the diaphragm stretches or un-stretches.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In a circuit, a capacitor can behave differently at different time instants.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The simplest model of a capacitor consists of two thin parallel conductive plates each with an area of A separated by a uniform gap of thickness d filled with a dielectric of permittivity ⁠ $\varepsilon$ ⁠.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] It is assumed the gap d is much smaller than the dimensions of the plates.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] This model applies well to many practical capacitors which are constructed of metal sheets separated by a thin layer of insulating dielectric, since manufacturers try to keep the dielectric very uniform in thickness to avoid thin spots which can cause failure of the capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] This "fringing field" area is approximately the same width as the plate separation, ⁠ d ⁠, and assuming d is small compared to the plate dimensions, it is small enough to be ignored.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] From Gauss's law the magnitude of the electric field between the plates is ⁠ $\textstyle E={\sigma \over \varepsilon }$ ⁠.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Therefore, in a capacitor the highest capacitance is achieved with a high permittivity dielectric material, large plate area, and small separation between the plates.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Since the area A of the plates increases with the square of the linear dimensions and the separation d increases linearly, the capacitance scales with the linear dimension of a capacitor (⁠ $C\varpropto L$ ⁠), or as the cube root of the volume.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] A parallel plate capacitor can only store a finite amount of energy before dielectric breakdown occurs.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The capacitor's dielectric material has a dielectric strength *U*d which sets the capacitor's breakdown voltage at *V* = *V*bd = *U*d*d*.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The maximum energy is a function of dielectric volume, permittivity, and dielectric strength.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Changing the plate area and the separation between the plates while maintaining the same volume causes no change of the maximum amount of energy that the capacitor can store, so long as the distance between plates remains much smaller than both the length and width of the plates.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In addition, these equations assume that the electric field is entirely concentrated in the dielectric between the plates.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In reality there are fringing fields outside the dielectric, for example between the sides of the capacitor plates, which increase the effective capacitance of the capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] This is sometimes called parasitic capacitance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] For some simple capacitor geometries this additional capacitance term can be calculated analytically.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] It becomes negligibly small when the ratios of plate width to separation and length to separation are large.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] For n number of plates in a capacitor, the total capacitance would be $C=\varepsilon _{o}{\frac {A}{d}}(n-1)$ where ${\textstyle C={\frac {\varepsilon _{o}A}{d}}}$ is the capacitance for a single plate and n is the number of interleaved plates.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] As shown to the figure on the right, the interleaved plates can be seen as parallel plates connected to each other.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Every pair of adjacent plates acts as a separate capacitor; the number of pairs is always one less than the number of plates, hence the $(n-1)$ multiplier.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] To increase the charge and voltage on a capacitor, work must be done by an external power source to move charge from the negative to the positive plate against the opposing force of the electric field.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] If the voltage on the capacitor is ⁠ V ⁠, the work $\mathrm {d} W$ required to move a small increment of charge $\mathrm {d} q$ from the negative to the positive plate is ⁠ $\mathrm {d} W=V\mathop {} \!\mathrm {d} q$ ⁠.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The energy is stored in the increased electric field between the plates.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] This potential energy will remain in the capacitor until the charge is removed.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] If charge is allowed to move back from the positive to the negative plate, for example by connecting a circuit with resistance between the plates, the charge moving under the influence of the electric field will do work on the external circuit.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] If the gap between the capacitor plates d is constant, as in the parallel plate model above, the electric field between the plates will be uniform (neglecting fringing fields) and will have a constant value ⁠ $E=V/d$ ⁠.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The current $I(t)$ through any component in an electric circuit is defined as the rate of flow of a charge $Q(t)$ passing through it.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Actual charges – electrons – cannot pass through the dielectric of an *ideal* capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Rather, one electron accumulates on the negative plate for each one that leaves the positive plate, resulting in an electron depletion and consequent positive charge on one electrode that is equal and opposite to the accumulated negative charge on the other.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Thus the charge on the electrodes is equal to the integral of the current as well as proportional to the voltage, as discussed above.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] As with any antiderivative, a constant of integration is added to represent the initial voltage ⁠ $V(t_{0})$ ⁠).
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] for C independent of time, voltage and electric charge.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The dual of the capacitor is the inductor, which stores energy in a magnetic field rather than an electric field.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Its current-voltage relation is obtained by exchanging current and voltage in the capacitor equations and replacing C with the inductance L.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] A series circuit containing only a resistor, a capacitor, a switch and a constant DC source of voltage *V*0 is known as a *charging circuit*.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] At *t* = 0, the voltage across the capacitor is zero and the voltage across the resistor is *V*0.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The initial current is then ⁠ $\textstyle I(0)={V_{0} \over R}$ ⁠.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] As the capacitor reaches equilibrium with the source voltage, the voltages across the resistor and the current through the entire circuit decay exponentially.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In the case of a *discharging* capacitor, the capacitor's initial voltage (*V*Ci) replaces *V*0.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Impedance, the vector sum of reactance and resistance, describes the phase difference and the ratio of amplitudes between sinusoidally varying voltage and sinusoidally varying current at a given frequency.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Fourier analysis allows any signal to be constructed from a spectrum of frequencies, whence the circuit's reaction to the various frequencies may be found.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The ⁠ $-j$ ⁠ phase indicates that the AC voltage ⁠ $V=ZI$ ⁠ lags the AC current by 90°: the positive current phase corresponds to increasing voltage as the capacitor charges; zero current corresponds to instantaneous constant voltage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Impedance decreases with increasing capacitance and increasing frequency.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] This implies that a higher-frequency signal or a larger capacitor results in a lower voltage amplitude per current amplitude – an AC "short circuit" or AC coupling.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Conversely, for very low frequencies, the reactance is high, so that a capacitor is nearly an open circuit in AC analysis – those frequencies have been "filtered out".
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are different from resistors and inductors in that the impedance is *inversely* proportional to the defining characteristic; i.e., capacitance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] A capacitor connected to an alternating voltage source has a displacement current to flowing through it.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] At ⁠ $\sin(\omega t)=-1$ ⁠, the capacitor has a maximum (or peak) current whereby ⁠ $I_{0}=\omega CV_{0}$ ⁠.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In this situation, the current is out of phase with the voltage by ⁠ $\textstyle +{\pi \over 2}$ ⁠ radians or +90 degrees, i.e. the current leads the voltage by 90°.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Capacitors in a parallel configuration each have the same applied voltage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Charge is apportioned among them by capacitance value.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Connected in series, the schematic diagram reveals that the separation distance, not the plate area, adds up.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The capacitors each store instantaneous charge build-up equal to that of every other capacitor in the series.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The total voltage difference from end to end is apportioned to each capacitor according to the inverse of its capacitance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are combined in series to achieve a higher working voltage, for example for smoothing a high voltage power supply.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The voltage ratings, which are based on plate separation, add up, if capacitance and leakage currents for each capacitor are identical.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In such an application, on occasion, series strings are connected in parallel, forming a matrix.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The goal is to maximize the energy storage of the network without overloading any capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] For high-energy storage with capacitors in series, some safety considerations must be applied to ensure one capacitor failing and leaking current does not apply too much voltage to the other series capacitors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Series connection is also sometimes used to adapt polarized electrolytic capacitors for bipolar AC use.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] (Note that this is only correct if all capacitance values are equal).
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In practice, capacitors deviate from the ideal capacitor equation in several aspects.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Some of these, such as leakage current and parasitic effects are linear, or can be analyzed as nearly linear, and can be accounted for by adding virtual components to form an equivalent circuit.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The usual methods of network analysis can then be applied.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In other cases, such as with breakdown voltage, the effect is non-linear and ordinary (normal, e.g., linear) network analysis cannot be used, the effect must be considered separately.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Yet another group of artifacts may exist, including temperature dependence, that may be linear but invalidates the assumption in the analysis that capacitance is a constant.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Finally, combined parasitic effects such as inherent inductance, resistance, or dielectric losses can exhibit non-uniform behavior at varying frequencies of operation.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Above a particular electric field strength, known as the dielectric strength ⁠ $E_{\mathrm {ds} }$ ⁠, the dielectric in a capacitor becomes conductive.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The maximum energy that can be stored safely in a capacitor is limited by the breakdown voltage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Exceeding this voltage can result in a short circuit between the plates, which can often cause permanent damage to the dielectric, plates, or both.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Due to the scaling of capacitance and breakdown voltage with dielectric thickness, all capacitors made with a particular dielectric have approximately equal maximum energy density, to the extent that the dielectric dominates their volume.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] For air dielectric capacitors the breakdown field strength is of the order 2–5 MV/m (or equivalently in kilovolts per millimeter); for mica the breakdown is 100–300 MV/m; for oil, 15–25 MV/m; it can be much less when other materials are used for the dielectric.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The dielectric is used in very thin layers and so absolute breakdown voltage of capacitors is limited.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Typical ratings for capacitors used for general electronics applications range from a few volts to 1 kilovolt.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] As the voltage increases, the dielectric must be thicker, making high-voltage capacitors larger per capacitance than those rated for lower voltages.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The breakdown voltage is critically affected by factors such as the geometry of the capacitor conductive parts; sharp edges or points increase the electric field strength at that point and can lead to a local breakdown.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Once this starts to happen, the breakdown quickly tracks through the dielectric until it reaches the opposite plate, leaving carbon behind and causing a short (or relatively low resistance) circuit.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The results can be explosive, as the short in the capacitor draws current from the surrounding circuitry and dissipates the energy.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] However, in capacitors with particular dielectrics and thin metal electrodes, shorts are not formed after breakdown.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] It happens because a metal melts or evaporates in a breakdown vicinity, isolating it from the rest of the capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The usual breakdown route is that the field strength becomes large enough to pull electrons in the dielectric from their atoms thus causing conduction.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Other scenarios are possible, such as impurities in the dielectric, and, if the dielectric is of a crystalline nature, imperfections in the crystal structure can result in an avalanche breakdown as seen in semi-conductor devices.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Breakdown voltage is also affected by pressure, humidity and temperature.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] An ideal capacitor only stores and releases electrical energy, without dissipation.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] As frequency increases, the capacitive impedance (a negative reactance) reduces, so the dielectric's conductance becomes less important and the series components become more significant.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Thus, a simplified RLC series model valid for a large frequency range simply treats the capacitor as being in series with an equivalent series inductance ${\text{ESL}}$ and a frequency-dependent *equivalent series resistance* ${\text{ESR}}$ , which varies little with frequency.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Unlike the previous model, this model is not valid at DC and very low frequencies where $G_{\text{dielectric}}$ is relevant.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Inductive reactance increases with frequency.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Because its sign is positive, it counteracts the capacitance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] At the RLC circuit's natural frequency $\omega _{0}{=}{\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {{\text{ESL}}\cdot {\text{C}}}}}$ , the inductance perfectly cancels the capacitance, so total reactance is zero.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Since the total impedance at $\omega _{0}$ is just the real-value of ${\text{ESR}}$ , average power dissipation reaches its maximum of ⁠VRMS2/ESR⁠, where VRMS is the root mean square (RMS) voltage across the capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] At even higher frequencies, the inductive impedance dominates, so the capacitor undesirably behaves instead like an inductor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] High-frequency engineering involves accounting for the inductance of all connections and components.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The ⁠ Q ⁠ factor is a measure of its efficiency: the higher the ⁠ Q ⁠ factor of the capacitor, the closer it approaches the behavior of an ideal capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Ripple current is the AC component of an applied source (often a switched-mode power supply) whose frequency may be constant or varying.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Ripple current causes heat to be generated within the capacitor due to the dielectric losses caused by the changing field strength together with the current flow across the slightly resistive supply lines or the electrolyte in the capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The equivalent series resistance (ESR) is the amount of internal series resistance one would add to a perfect capacitor to model this.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Some types of capacitors, primarily tantalum and aluminum electrolytic capacitors, as well as some film capacitors have a specified rating value for maximum ripple current.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The capacitance of certain capacitors decreases as the component ages.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In ceramic capacitors, this is caused by degradation of the dielectric.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The type of dielectric, ambient operating and storage temperatures are the most significant aging factors, while the operating voltage usually has a smaller effect, i.e., usual capacitor design is to minimize voltage coefficient.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The aging process may be reversed by heating the component above the Curie point.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Aging is fastest near the beginning of life of the component, and the device stabilizes over time.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors age as the electrolyte evaporates.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In contrast with ceramic capacitors, this occurs towards the end of life of the component.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Temperature dependence of capacitance is usually expressed in parts per million (ppm) per °C.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] It can usually be taken as a broadly linear function but can be noticeably non-linear at the temperature extremes.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The temperature coefficient may be positive or negative, depending mostly on the dielectric material.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Some, designated C0G/NP0, but called **NPO**, have a somewhat negative coefficient at one temperature, positive at another, and zero in between.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Such components may be specified for temperature-critical circuits.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Capacitors, especially ceramic capacitors, and older designs such as paper capacitors, can absorb sound waves resulting in a microphonic effect.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Vibration moves the plates, causing the capacitance to vary, in turn inducing AC current.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Some dielectrics also generate piezoelectricity.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The resulting interference is especially problematic in audio applications, potentially causing feedback or unintended recording.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In the reverse microphonic effect, the varying electric field between the capacitor plates exerts a physical force, moving them as a speaker.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] This can generate audible sound, but drains energy and stresses the dielectric and the electrolyte, if any.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Current reversal occurs when the current changes direction.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Voltage reversal is the change of polarity in a circuit.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Reversal is generally described as the percentage of the maximum rated voltage that reverses polarity.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In DC circuits, this is usually less than 100%, often in the range of 0 to 90%, whereas AC circuits experience 100% reversal.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In DC circuits and pulsed circuits, current and voltage reversal are affected by the damping of the system.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Voltage reversal is encountered in RLC circuits that are underdamped.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The current and voltage reverse direction, forming a harmonic oscillator between the inductance and capacitance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The current and voltage tends to oscillate and may reverse direction several times, with each peak being lower than the previous, until the system reaches an equilibrium.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In comparison, critically damped or overdamped systems usually do not experience a voltage reversal.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Reversal is also encountered in AC circuits, where the peak current is equal in each direction.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] For maximum life, capacitors usually need to be able to handle the maximum amount of reversal that a system may experience.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] An AC circuit experiences 100% voltage reversal, while underdamped DC circuits experience less than 100%.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Reversal creates excess electric fields in the dielectric, causes excess heating of both the dielectric and the conductors, and can dramatically shorten the life expectancy of the capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Reversal ratings often affect the design considerations for the capacitor, from the choice of dielectric materials and voltage ratings to the types of internal connections used.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Capacitors made with any type of dielectric material show some level of "dielectric absorption" or "soakage".
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] On discharging a capacitor and disconnecting it, after a short time it may develop a voltage due to hysteresis in the dielectric.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] This effect is objectionable in applications such as precision sample and hold circuits or timing circuits.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The level of absorption depends on many factors, from design considerations to charging time, since the absorption is a time-dependent process.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] However, the primary factor is the type of dielectric material.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Capacitors such as tantalum electrolytic or polysulfone film exhibit relatively high absorption, while polystyrene or Teflon allow very small levels of absorption.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In some capacitors where dangerous voltages and energies exist, such as in flashtubes, television sets, microwave ovens and defibrillators, the dielectric absorption can recharge the capacitor to hazardous voltages after it has been shorted or discharged.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Any capacitor containing over 10 joules of energy is generally considered hazardous, while 50 joules or higher is potentially lethal.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] A capacitor may regain anywhere from 0.01 to 20% of its original charge over a period of several minutes, allowing a seemingly safe capacitor to become surprisingly dangerous.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] No material is a perfect insulator, thus all dielectrics allow some small level of current to leak through, which can be measured with a megohmmeter.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Leakage is equivalent to a resistor in parallel with the capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Constant exposure to factors such as heat, mechanical stress, or humidity can cause the dielectric to deteriorate resulting in excessive leakage, a problem often seen in older vacuum tube circuits, particularly where oiled paper and foil capacitors were used.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In many vacuum tube circuits, interstage coupling capacitors are used to conduct a varying signal from the plate of one tube to the grid circuit of the next stage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] A leaky capacitor can cause the grid circuit voltage to be raised from its normal bias setting, causing excessive current or signal distortion in the downstream tube.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] In power amplifiers this can cause the plates to glow red, or current limiting resistors to overheat, even fail.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Similar considerations apply to component fabricated solid-state (transistor) amplifiers, but, owing to lower heat production and the use of modern polyester dielectric-barriers, this once-common problem has become relatively rare.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors are *conditioned* when manufactured by applying a voltage sufficient to initiate the proper internal chemical state.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] This state is maintained by regular use of the equipment.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] If a system using electrolytic capacitors is unused for a long period of time it can lose its conditioning.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Sometimes they fail with a short circuit when next operated.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] All capacitors have varying lifespans, depending upon their construction, operational conditions, and environmental conditions.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Solid-state ceramic capacitors generally have very long lives under normal use, which has little dependency on factors such as vibration or ambient temperature, but factors like humidity, mechanical stress, and fatigue play a primary role in their failure.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Some capacitors may experience a gradual loss of capacitance, increased leakage or an increase in equivalent series resistance (ESR), while others may fail suddenly or even catastrophically.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] For example, metal-film capacitors are more prone to damage from stress and humidity, but will self-heal when a breakdown in the dielectric occurs.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The formation of a glow discharge at the point of failure prevents arcing by vaporizing the metallic film in that spot, neutralizing any short circuit with minimal loss in capacitance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] When enough pinholes accumulate in the film, a total failure occurs in a metal-film capacitor, generally happening suddenly without warning.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors generally have the shortest lifespans.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors are affected very little by vibration or humidity, but factors such as ambient and operational temperatures play a large role in their failure, which gradually occur as an increase in ESR (up to 300%) and as much as a 20% decrease in capacitance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] The capacitors contain electrolytes which will eventually diffuse through the seals and evaporate.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] An increase in temperature also increases internal pressure, and increases the reaction rate of the chemicals.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] Manufacturers often use this equation to supply an expected lifespan, in hours, for electrolytic capacitors when used at their designed operating temperature, which is affected by both ambient temperature, ESR, and ripple current.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p01] However, these ideal conditions may not exist in every use.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Practical capacitors are available commercially in many different forms.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The type of internal dielectric, the structure of the plates and the device packaging all strongly affect the characteristics of the capacitor, and its applications.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Values available range from very low (picofarad range; while arbitrarily low values are in principle possible, stray (parasitic) capacitance in any circuit is the limiting factor) to about 5 kF supercapacitors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Above approximately 1 microfarad electrolytic capacitors are usually used because of their small size and low cost compared with other types, unless their relatively poor stability, life and polarised nature make them unsuitable.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Very high capacity supercapacitors use a porous carbon-based electrode material.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors have a dielectric spacer, which increases their capacitance compared to air or a vacuum.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] In order to maximise the charge that a capacitor can hold, the dielectric material needs to have as high a permittivity as possible, while also having as high a breakdown voltage as possible.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The dielectric also needs to have as low a loss with frequency as possible.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] However, low value capacitors are available with a high vacuum between their plates to allow extremely high voltage operation and low losses.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Variable capacitors with their plates open to the atmosphere were commonly used in radio tuning circuits.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Later designs use polymer foil dielectric between the moving and stationary plates, with no significant air space between the plates.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Several solid dielectrics are available, including paper, plastic, glass, mica and ceramic.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Paper was used extensively in older capacitors and offers relatively high voltage performance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] However, paper absorbs moisture, and has been largely replaced by plastic film capacitors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Large plastic film capacitors are used extensively in suppression circuits, motor start circuits, and power-factor correction circuits.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Ceramic capacitors are generally small, cheap and useful for high frequency applications, although their capacitance varies strongly with voltage and temperature and they age poorly.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] They can also suffer from the piezoelectric effect.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Ceramic capacitors are broadly categorized as class 1 dielectrics, which have predictable variation of capacitance with temperature or class 2 dielectrics, which can operate at higher voltage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Modern multilayer ceramics are usually quite small, but some types have inherently wide value tolerances, microphonic issues, and are usually physically brittle.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Glass and mica capacitors are extremely reliable, stable and tolerant to high temperatures and voltages, but are too expensive for most mainstream applications.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors use an aluminum or tantalum plate with an oxide dielectric layer.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The second electrode is a liquid electrolyte, connected to the circuit by another foil plate.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors offer very high capacitance but suffer from poor tolerances, high instability, gradual loss of capacitance especially when subjected to heat, and high leakage current.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Poor quality capacitors may leak electrolyte, which is harmful to printed circuit boards.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The conductivity of the electrolyte drops at low temperatures, which increases equivalent series resistance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] While widely used for power-supply conditioning, poor high-frequency characteristics make them unsuitable for many applications.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors suffer from self-degradation if unused for a period (around a year), and when full power is applied may short circuit, permanently damaging the capacitor and usually blowing a fuse or causing failure of rectifier diodes.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] For example, in older equipment, this may cause arcing in rectifier tubes.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] They can be restored before use by gradually applying the operating voltage, often performed on antique vacuum tube equipment over a period of thirty minutes by using a variable transformer to supply AC power.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The use of this technique may be less satisfactory for some solid state equipment, which may be damaged by operation below its normal power range, requiring that the power supply first be isolated from the consuming circuits.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Such remedies may not be applicable to modern high-frequency power supplies as these produce full output voltage even with reduced input.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Tantalum capacitors offer better frequency and temperature characteristics than aluminum, but higher dielectric absorption and leakage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Polymer capacitors (OS-CON, OC-CON, KO, AO) use solid conductive polymer (or polymerized organic semiconductor) as electrolyte and offer longer life and lower ESR at higher cost than standard electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] A feedthrough capacitor is a component that, while not serving as its main use, has capacitance and is used to conduct signals through a conductive sheet.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Several other types of capacitor are available for specialist applications.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Supercapacitors store large amounts of energy.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Supercapacitors made from carbon aerogel, carbon nanotubes, or highly porous electrode materials, offer extremely high capacitance (up to 5 kF as of 2010) and can be used in some applications instead of rechargeable batteries.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Alternating current capacitors are specifically designed to work on line (mains) voltage AC power circuits.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] They are commonly used in electric motor circuits and are often designed to handle large currents, so they tend to be physically large.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] They are usually ruggedly packaged, often in metal cases that can be easily grounded/earthed.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] They also are designed with direct current breakdown voltages of at least five times the maximum AC voltage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The dielectric constant for a number of very useful dielectrics changes as a function of the applied electrical field, for example ferroelectric materials, so the capacitance for these devices is more complex.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] This field polarizes the dielectric, which polarization, in the case of a ferroelectric, is a nonlinear *S*-shaped function of the electric field, which, in the case of a large area parallel plate device, translates into a capacitance that is a nonlinear function of the voltage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Corresponding to the voltage-dependent capacitance, to charge the capacitor to voltage V an integral relation is found: $Q=\int _{0}^{V}C(V)\mathop {} \!\mathrm {d} V$ which agrees with *Q* = *CV* only when C does not depend on voltage V.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The nonlinear capacitance of a microscope probe scanned along a ferroelectric surface is used to study the domain structure of ferroelectric materials.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Another example of voltage dependent capacitance occurs in semiconductor devices such as semiconductor diodes, where the voltage dependence stems not from a change in dielectric constant but in a voltage dependence of the spacing between the charges on the two sides of the capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] This effect is intentionally exploited in diode-like devices known as varicaps.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] If a capacitor is driven with a time-varying voltage that changes rapidly enough, at some frequency the polarization of the dielectric cannot follow the voltage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] As an example of the origin of this mechanism, the internal microscopic dipoles contributing to the dielectric constant cannot move instantly, and so as frequency of an applied alternating voltage increases, the dipole response is limited and the dielectric constant diminishes.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] A changing dielectric constant with frequency is referred to as dielectric dispersion, and is governed by dielectric relaxation processes, such as Debye relaxation.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] indicating the lag in response by the time dependence of *εr*, calculated in principle from an underlying microscopic analysis, for example, of the dipole behavior in the dielectric.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] See, for example, linear response function.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The integral extends over the entire past history up to the present time.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] where *ε*r(*ω*) is now a complex function, with an imaginary part related to absorption of energy from the field by the medium.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The capacitance, being proportional to the dielectric constant, also exhibits this frequency behavior.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] (Measurement "without the dielectric" in principle means measurement in free space, an unattainable goal inasmuch as even the quantum vacuum is predicted to exhibit nonideal behavior, such as dichroism.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Using this measurement method, the dielectric constant may exhibit a resonance at certain frequencies corresponding to characteristic response frequencies (excitation energies) of contributors to the dielectric constant.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] These resonances are the basis for a number of experimental techniques for detecting defects.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The *conductance method* measures absorption as a function of frequency.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Alternatively, the time response of the capacitance can be used directly, as in *deep-level transient spectroscopy*.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Another example of frequency dependent capacitance occurs with MOS capacitors, where the slow generation of minority carriers means that at high frequencies the capacitance measures only the majority carrier response, while at low frequencies both types of carrier respond.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] At optical frequencies, in semiconductors the dielectric constant exhibits structure related to the band structure of the solid.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Sophisticated modulation spectroscopy measurement methods based upon modulating the crystal structure by pressure or by other stresses and observing the related changes in absorption or reflection of light have advanced our knowledge of these materials.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The arrangement of plates and dielectric has many variations in different styles depending on the desired ratings of the capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] For small values of capacitance (microfarads and less), ceramic disks use metallic coatings, with wire leads bonded to the coating.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Larger values can be made by multiple stacks of plates and disks.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Larger value capacitors usually use a metal foil or metal film layer deposited on the surface of a dielectric film to make the plates, and a dielectric film of impregnated paper or plastic – these are rolled up to save space.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] To reduce the series resistance and inductance for long plates, the plates and dielectric are staggered so that connection is made at the common edge of the rolled-up plates, not at the ends of the foil or metalized film strips that comprise the plates.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The assembly is encased to prevent moisture entering the dielectric – early radio equipment used a cardboard tube sealed with wax.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Modern paper or film dielectric capacitors are dipped in a hard thermoplastic.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Large capacitors for high-voltage use may have the roll form compressed to fit into a rectangular metal case, with bolted terminals and bushings for connections.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The dielectric in larger capacitors is often impregnated with a liquid to improve its properties.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may have their connecting leads arranged in many configurations, for example axially or radially.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] "Axial" means that the leads are on a common axis, typically the axis of the capacitor's cylindrical body – the leads extend from opposite ends.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Radial leads are rarely aligned along radii of the body's circle, so the term is conventional.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The leads (until bent) are usually in planes parallel to that of the flat body of the capacitor, and extend in the same direction; they are often parallel as manufactured.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Small, cheap discoidal ceramic capacitors have existed from the 1930s onward, and remain in widespread use.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] After the 1980s, surface mount packages for capacitors have been widely used.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] These packages are extremely small and lack connecting leads, allowing them to be soldered directly onto the surface of printed circuit boards.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Surface mount components avoid undesirable high-frequency effects due to the leads and simplify automated assembly, although manual handling is made difficult due to their small size.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Mechanically controlled variable capacitors allow the plate spacing to be adjusted, for example by rotating or sliding a set of movable plates into alignment with a set of stationary plates.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Low cost variable capacitors squeeze together alternating layers of aluminum and plastic with a screw.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Electrical control of capacitance is achievable with varactors (or varicaps), which are reverse-biased semiconductor diodes whose depletion region width varies with applied voltage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] They are used in phase-locked loops, amongst other applications.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors have designations printed on their bodies to indicate their electrical characteristics.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors, such as electrolytic types usually display the capacitance as value with explicit unit, for example, *220 μF*.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] For typographical reasons, some manufacturers print *MF* on capacitors to indicate microfarads (μF).
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Smaller capacitors, such as ceramic types, often use a shorthand-notation consisting of three digits and an optional letter, where the digits (*XYZ*) denote the capacitance in picofarad (pF), calculated as *XY* × 10*Z*, and the letter indicating the tolerance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Common tolerances are ±5%, ±10%, and ±20%, denoted as J, K, and M, respectively.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] A capacitor may also be labeled with its working voltage, temperature, and other relevant characteristics.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Example: A capacitor labeled or designated as *473K 330V* has a capacitance of 47×103 pF = 47 nF (±10%) with a maximum working voltage of 330 V.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The working voltage of a capacitor is nominally the highest voltage that may be applied across it without undue risk of breaking down the dielectric layer.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The code consists of an uppercase letter denoting the two significant digits of the value followed by a digit indicating the multiplier.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The EIA standard also defines a number of lowercase letters to specify a number of values not found in E24.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The RKM code following IEC 60062 and BS 1852 is a notation to state a capacitor's value in a circuit diagram.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] It avoids using a decimal separator and replaces the decimal separator with the SI prefix symbol for the particular value (and the letter F for weight 1).
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The code is also used for part markings.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] In texts prior to the 1960s and on some capacitor packages until more recently, obsolete capacitance units were utilized in electronic books, magazines, and electronics catalogs.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The old units "mfd" and "mf" meant *microfarad* (μF); and the old units "mmfd", "mmf", "uuf", "μμf", "pfd" meant *picofarad* (pF); but they are rarely used any more.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Also, "Micromicrofarad" or "micro-microfarad" are obsolete units that are found in some older texts that is equivalent to *picofarad* (pF).
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can store electric energy when disconnected from its charging circuit, so it can be used like a temporary battery, or like other types of rechargeable energy storage system.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are commonly used in electronic devices to maintain power supply while batteries are being changed.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can facilitate conversion of kinetic energy of charged particles into electric energy and store it.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] There are tradeoffs between capacitors and batteries as storage devices.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Without external resistors or inductors, capacitors can generally release their stored energy in a very short time compared to batteries.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Conversely, batteries can hold a far greater charge per their size.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Conventional capacitors provide less than 360 joules per kilogram of specific energy, whereas a conventional alkaline battery has a density of 590 kJ/kg.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] There is an intermediate solution: supercapacitors, which can accept and deliver charge much faster than batteries, and tolerate many more charge and discharge cycles than rechargeable batteries.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] They are, however, 10 times larger than conventional batteries for a given charge.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] On the other hand, it has been shown that the amount of charge stored in the dielectric layer of the thin film capacitor can be equal to, or can even exceed, the amount of charge stored on its plates.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] In car audio systems, large capacitors store energy for the amplifier to use on demand.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Also, for a flash tube, a capacitor is used to hold the high voltage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] In the 1930s, John Atanasoff applied the principle of energy storage in capacitors to construct dynamic digital memories for the first binary computers that used electron tubes for logic.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Pulsed power is used in many applications to increase the power intensity (watts) of a volume of energy (joules) by releasing that volume within a very short time.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Pulses in the nanosecond range and powers in the gigawatts are achievable.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Short pulses often require specially constructed, low-inductance, high-voltage capacitors that are often used in large groups (*capacitor banks*) to supply huge pulses of current for many pulsed power applications.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] These include electromagnetic forming, Marx generators, pulsed lasers (especially TEA lasers), pulse forming networks, radar, fusion research, and particle accelerators.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Large capacitor banks (reservoir) are used as energy sources for the exploding-bridgewire detonators or slapper detonators in nuclear weapons and other specialty weapons.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Experimental work is under way using banks of capacitors as power sources for electromagnetic armour and electromagnetic railguns and coilguns.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Reservoir capacitors are used in power supplies where they smooth the output of a full or half wave rectifier.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] They can also be used in charge pump circuits as the energy storage element in the generation of higher voltages than the input voltage.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are connected in parallel with the power circuits of most electronic devices and larger systems (such as factories) to shunt away and conceal current fluctuations from the primary power source to provide a "clean" power supply for signal or control circuits.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Audio equipment, for example, uses several capacitors in this way, to shunt away power line hum before it gets into the signal circuitry.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The capacitors act as a local reserve for the DC power source, and bypass AC currents from the power supply.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] This is used in car audio applications, when a stiffening capacitor compensates for the inductance and resistance of the leads to the lead–acid car battery.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] In electric power distribution, capacitors are used for power-factor correction.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Such capacitors often come as three capacitors connected as a three phase load.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Usually, the values of these capacitors are not given in farads but rather as a reactive power in volt-amperes reactive (var).
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The purpose is to counteract inductive loading from devices like electric motors and transmission lines to make the load appear to be mostly resistive.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Individual motor or lamp loads may have capacitors for power-factor correction, or larger sets of capacitors (usually with automatic switching devices) may be installed at a load center within a building or in a large utility substation.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Because capacitors pass AC but block DC signals (when charged up to the applied DC voltage), they are often used to separate the AC and DC components of a signal.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] This method is known as *AC coupling* or "capacitive coupling".
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Here, a large value of capacitance, whose value need not be accurately controlled, but whose reactance is small at the signal frequency, is employed.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] A decoupling capacitor is a capacitor used to protect one part of a circuit from the effect of another, for instance to suppress noise or transients.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Noise caused by other circuit elements is shunted through the capacitor, reducing the effect they have on the rest of the circuit.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] It is most commonly used between the power supply and ground.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] An alternative name is *bypass capacitor* as it is used to bypass the power supply or other high impedance component of a circuit.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Decoupling capacitors need not always be discrete components.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used in these applications may be built into a printed circuit board, between the various layers.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] These are often referred to as embedded capacitors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The layers in the board contributing to the capacitive properties also function as power and ground planes, and have a dielectric in between them, enabling them to operate as a parallel plate capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] When an inductive circuit is opened, the current through the inductance collapses quickly, creating a large voltage across the open circuit of the switch or relay.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] If the inductance is large enough, the energy may generate a spark, causing the contact points to oxidize, deteriorate, or sometimes weld together, or destroying a solid-state switch.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] A snubber capacitor across the newly opened circuit creates a path for this impulse to bypass the contact points, thereby preserving their life; these were commonly found in contact breaker ignition systems, for instance.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Similarly, in smaller scale circuits, the spark may not be enough to damage the switch but may still radiate undesirable radio frequency interference (RFI), which a filter capacitor absorbs.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Snubber capacitors are usually employed with a low-value resistor in series, to dissipate energy and minimize RFI.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Such resistor-capacitor combinations are available in a single package.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are also used in parallel with interrupting units of a high-voltage circuit breaker to equally distribute the voltage between these units.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] In schematic diagrams, a capacitor used primarily for DC charge storage is often drawn vertically in circuit diagrams with the lower, more negative, plate drawn as an arc.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The straight plate indicates the positive terminal of the device, if it is polarized (see electrolytic capacitor).
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] In single phase squirrel cage motors, the primary winding within the motor housing is not capable of starting a rotational motion on the rotor, but is capable of sustaining one.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] To start the motor, a secondary "start" winding has a series non-polarized *starting capacitor* to introduce a lead in the sinusoidal current.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] When the secondary (start) winding is placed at an angle with respect to the primary (run) winding, a rotating electric field is created.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The force of the rotational field is not constant, but is sufficient to start the rotor spinning.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] When the rotor comes close to operating speed, a centrifugal switch (or current-sensitive relay in series with the main winding) disconnects the capacitor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The start capacitor is typically mounted to the side of the motor housing.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] These are called capacitor-start motors, that have relatively high starting torque.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Typically they can have up-to four times as much starting torque as a split-phase motor and are used on applications such as compressors, pressure washers and any small device requiring high starting torques.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitor-run induction motors have a permanently connected phase-shifting capacitor in series with a second winding.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The motor is much like a two-phase induction motor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Motor-starting capacitors are typically non-polarized electrolytic types, while running capacitors are conventional paper or plastic film dielectric types.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The energy stored in a capacitor can be used to represent information, either in binary form, as in DRAMs, or in analogue form, as in analog sampled filters and CCDs.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors can be used in analog circuits as components of integrators or more complex filters and in negative feedback loop stabilization.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Signal processing circuits also use capacitors to integrate a current signal.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors and inductors are applied together in tuned circuits to select information in particular frequency bands.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] For example, radio receivers rely on variable capacitors to tune the station frequency.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Speakers use passive analog crossovers, and analog equalizers use capacitors to select different audio bands.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The resonant frequency *f* of a tuned circuit is a function of the inductance (*L*) and capacitance (*C*) in series, and is given by: $f={\frac {1}{2\pi {\sqrt {LC}}}}$ where L is in henries and C is in farads.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors are designed to maintain a fixed physical structure.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] However, various factors can change the structure of the capacitor, and the resulting change in capacitance can be used to sense those factors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors with an exposed and porous dielectric can be used to measure humidity in air.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] ; as the fuel covers more of a pair of plates, the circuit capacitance increases.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Squeezing the dielectric can change a capacitor at a few tens of bar pressure sufficiently that it can be used as a pressure sensor.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] A selected, but otherwise standard, polymer dielectric capacitor, when immersed in a compatible gas or liquid, can work usefully as a very low cost pressure sensor up to many hundreds of bar.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors with a flexible plate can be used to measure strain or pressure.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] use pressure-sensing diaphragms, which form a capacitor plate of an oscillator circuit.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] , where one plate is moved by air pressure, relative to the fixed position of the other plate.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] capacitors etched on a chip to measure the magnitude and direction of the acceleration vector.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] deployment, and in many other applications.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] musical instrument by moving their hand since this changes the effective capacitance between the user's hand and the antenna.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] are used on many consumer electronic products.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can possess spring-like qualities in an oscillator circuit.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] In the image example, a capacitor acts to influence the biasing voltage at the npn transistor's base.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The resistance values of the voltage-divider resistors and the capacitance value of the capacitor together control the oscillatory frequency.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] A light-emitting capacitor is made from a dielectric that uses phosphorescence to produce light.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] If one of the conductive plates is made with a transparent material, the light is visible.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Light-emitting capacitors are used in the construction of electroluminescent panels, for applications such as backlighting for laptop computers.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] In this case, the entire panel is a capacitor used for the purpose of generating light.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] The hazards posed by a capacitor are usually determined by the amount of energy stored, which can cause electrical burns or heart fibrillation.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Factors such as voltage and chassis material are of secondary consideration, which are more related to how easily a shock can be initiated rather than how much damage can occur.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Shocks over ten joules generally damage skin, and are considered hazardous.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Any capacitor that can store 50 joules or more is considered potentially lethal.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may retain a charge long after power is removed from a circuit; this charge can cause dangerous or fatal shocks or damage connected equipment.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] For example, the flash of a disposable camera has a photoflash capacitor that may contain over 15 joules of energy and be charged to over 300 volts.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Service procedures for electronic devices usually include instructions to discharge large or high-voltage capacitors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors may have built-in discharge resistors to dissipate stored energy to a safe level within a few seconds after power is removed.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] High-voltage capacitors are stored with the terminals shorted, as protection from potentially dangerous voltages due to dielectric absorption or from transient voltages the capacitor may pick up from static charges or passing weather events.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Some old, large oil-filled paper or plastic film capacitors contain polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) which can leak into groundwater from landfills.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors containing PCBs were labelled as containing "Askarel" and several other trade names.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] PCB-filled paper capacitors are found in pre-1975 fluorescent lamp ballasts, and other applications.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Such capacitors may be sealed in a metal can with ceramic feed-through connectors.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may catastrophically fail when subjected to voltages or currents beyond their rating, or in case of polarized capacitors, applied in a reverse polarity.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Failures may create arcing that heats and vaporizes the dielectric fluid, causing a build up of pressurized gas that may result in swelling, rupture, or an explosion.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors may have vents or similar mechanism to release of pressure in the event of failure.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used in RF or sustained high-current applications can overheat, especially in the center of the capacitor rolls.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used within high-energy capacitor banks can violently explode when a short in one capacitor causes sudden dumping of energy stored in the rest of the bank into the failing unit.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] High voltage vacuum capacitors can generate soft X-rays even during normal operation.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] Proper containment, fusing, and preventive maintenance can help to minimize these hazards.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] High-voltage capacitors may benefit from a pre-charge to limit in-rush currents at power-up of high voltage direct current (HVDC) circuits.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p02] This extends the life of the component and may mitigate high-voltage hazards.
[src:electronics/capacitor-p03] The resonant frequency *f* of a tuned circuit is a function of the inductance (*L*) and capacitance (*C*) in series, and is given by: f = 1 2 π L C {\displaystyle f={\frac {1}{2\pi {\sqrt {LC}}}}} ({\displaystyle f={\frac {1}{2\pi {\sqrt {LC}}}}}) where L is in henries and C is in farads.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] In electronics, a **digital-to-analog converter** (**DAC**, **D/A**, **D2A**, or **D-to-A**) is a system that converts a digital signal into an analog signal.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] An analog-to-digital converter (ADC) performs the reverse function.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] DACs are commonly used in music players to convert digital data streams into analog audio signals.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] They are also used in televisions and mobile phones to convert digital video data into analog video signals.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] These two applications use DACs at opposite ends of the frequency/resolution trade-off.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The audio DAC is a low-frequency, high-resolution type, while the video DAC is a high-frequency low- to medium-resolution type.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] There are several DAC architectures; the suitability of a DAC for a particular application is determined by figures of merit, including: resolution, maximum sampling frequency and others.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Digital-to-analog conversion can degrade a signal, so a DAC should be specified that has insignificant errors in terms of the application.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Due to the complexity and the need for precisely matched components, all but the most specialized DACs are implemented as integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Discrete DACs (circuits constructed from multiple discrete electronic components instead of a packaged IC) would typically be extremely high-speed, low-resolution, power-hungry types, as used in military radar systems.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Very high-speed test equipment, especially sampling oscilloscopes, may also use discrete DACs.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] A DAC converts an abstract finite-precision number (usually a fixed-point binary number) into a physical quantity (e.g., a voltage or a pressure).
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] In particular, DACs are often used to convert finite-precision time series data to a continually varying physical signal.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Provided that a signal's bandwidth meets the requirements of the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem (i.e., a baseband signal with bandwidth less than the Nyquist frequency) and was sampled with infinite resolution, the original signal can theoretically be reconstructed from the sampled data.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] However, an ADC's filtering can't *entirely* eliminate all frequencies above the Nyquist frequency, which will alias into the baseband frequency range.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] And the ADC's digital sampling process introduces some quantization error (rounding error), which manifests as low-level noise.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] These errors can be kept within the requirements of the targeted application (e.g. under the limited dynamic range of human hearing for audio applications).
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] In a typical telephone call, a microphone converts speech into an analog electrical signal, which is digitized by an ADC.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The resulting digital data can be multiplexed with other digital information for transmission over a shared communication system.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] At the receiving end, a DAC converts the digital signal back into analog form so it can be amplified and reproduced as sound.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Early CD players used oversampling ahead of the D/A converter so that the analog reconstruction filter could be of low order and have a well-controlled phase response.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] In 1982, Philips described such a system in detail.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] A 16-bit, 44.1 kHz input is first applied to a digital interpolation filter and oversampled by a factor of four to 176.4 kHz.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The interpolation filter is a 96-tap finite impulse response network.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Its passband extends over the audio range, while the stopband attenuates the image components that would otherwise appear between 22 kHz and 88 kHz after zero-order hold conversion.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The higher sampling rate shifts these images away from the audio band and reduces the requirements on the analog filter.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The filtered sequence is then represented with 14-bit precision and applied to the Philips TDA1540.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] This converter employs segmented current sources.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The larger current elements are subdivided and switched in a manner that averages element errors over time, an early form of dynamic element matching.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The result is improved linearity compared with a straightforward binary-weighted current source.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] At the output of the converter, the waveform consists of a staircase approximation to the desired signal, together with residual high-frequency components from the sampling process.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] A third-order analog low-pass filter follows the converter.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] This filter removes the remaining out-of-band energy and provides the final smoothing of the waveform.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] A later device, the Philips TDA1541, provides full 16-bit resolution and removes the need for the intermediate word-length reduction step.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] In this and later designs, the same general arrangement was retained.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] This arrangement, digital interpolation followed by conversion and a relatively simple analog filter, became standard practice in CD playback and appears in later DACs such as the Crystal CS4397.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Most modern audio signals are stored in digital form (for example, MP3s and CDs), and in order to be heard through speakers, they must be converted into an analog signal.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] DACs are therefore found in CD players, digital music players, and PC sound cards.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Specialist standalone DACs can also be found in high-end hi-fi systems.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] These normally take the digital output of a compatible CD player or dedicated transport (which is basically a CD player with no internal DAC) and convert the signal into an analog line-level output that can then be fed into an amplifier to drive speakers.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Similar digital-to-analog converters can be found in digital speakers, such as USB speakers and in sound cards.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] In voice over IP applications, the source must first be digitized for transmission, so it undergoes conversion via an ADC and is then reconstructed into analog using a DAC on the receiving party's end.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Video signals from a digital source, such as a computer, must be converted to analog form if they are to be displayed on an analog monitor.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] As of 2007, analog inputs were more commonly used than digital, but this changed as flat-panel displays with DVI and/or HDMI connections became more widespread.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] A video DAC is, however, incorporated in any digital video player with analog outputs.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The DAC is usually integrated with some memory (RAM), which contains conversion tables for gamma correction, contrast and brightness, to make a device called a RAMDAC.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] A device that is distantly related to the DAC is the digitally controlled potentiometer, used to control an analog signal digitally.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] A one-bit mechanical actuator assumes two positions: one when on, another when off.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The motion of several one-bit actuators can be combined and weighted with a whiffletree mechanism to produce finer steps.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The IBM Selectric typewriter uses such a system.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] DACs are widely used in modern communication systems, enabling the generation of digitally defined transmission signals.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] High-speed DACs are used for mobile communications and ultra-high-speed DACs are employed in optical communications systems.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The number of possible output levels the DAC is designed to reproduce.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] , which is a measurement of the actual resolution attained by the DAC.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] The maximum speed at which the DACs circuitry can operate and still produce correct output.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] A measurement of the distortion and noise introduced to the signal by the DAC.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] and noise that accompanies the desired signal.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Other measurements, such as phase distortion and jitter, can also be very important for some applications, some of which (e.g., wireless data transmission, composite video) may even *rely* on accurate production of phase-adjusted signals.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] Non-linear PCM encodings (A-law / μ-law, ADPCM, NICAM) attempt to improve their effective dynamic ranges by using logarithmic step sizes between the output signal strengths represented by each data bit.
[src:electronics/digital-to-analog-converter] This trades greater quantization distortion of loud signals for better performance of quiet signals.
[src:electronics/diode] A **diode** is a two-terminal electronic component that conducts electric current primarily in one direction (asymmetric conductance).
[src:electronics/diode] It has low (ideally zero) resistance in one direction and high (ideally infinite) resistance in the other.
[src:electronics/diode] A semiconductor diode, the most commonly used type today, is a crystalline piece of semiconductor material with a p–n junction connected to two electrical terminals.
[src:electronics/diode] It has an exponential current–voltage characteristic.
[src:electronics/diode] Semiconductor diodes were the first semiconductor electronic devices.
[src:electronics/diode] The discovery of asymmetric electrical conduction across the contact between a crystalline mineral and a metal was made by German physicist Ferdinand Braun in 1874.
[src:electronics/diode] Today, most diodes are made of silicon, but other semiconducting materials such as gallium arsenide and germanium are also used.
[src:electronics/diode] The obsolete **thermionic diode** is a vacuum tube with two electrodes, a heated cathode and a plate, in which electrons can flow in only one direction, from the cathode to the plate.
[src:electronics/diode] Among many uses, diodes are found in rectifiers to convert alternating current (AC) power to direct current (DC), demodulation in radio receivers, and can even be used for logic or as temperature sensors.
[src:electronics/diode] A common variant of a diode is a light-emitting diode, which is used as electric lighting and status indicators on electronic devices.
[src:electronics/diode] The most common function of a diode is to allow an electric current to pass in one direction (called the diode's *forward* direction), while blocking it in the opposite direction (the *reverse* direction).
[src:electronics/diode] This unidirectional behavior can convert alternating current (AC) to direct current (DC), a process called rectification.
[src:electronics/diode] As rectifiers, diodes can be used for such tasks as extracting modulation from radio signals in radio receivers.
[src:electronics/diode] This voltage may loosely be referred to simply as the diode's *forward voltage drop* or just *voltage drop*, since a consequence of the steepness of the exponential is that a diode's voltage drop will not significantly exceed the threshold voltage under normal forward bias operating conditions.
[src:electronics/diode] Datasheets typically quote a typical or maximum *forward voltage* (VF) for a specified current and temperature (e.g.
[src:electronics/diode] 20 mA and 25 **°**C for LEDs), so the user has a guarantee about when a certain amount of current will kick in.
[src:electronics/diode] At higher currents, the forward voltage drop of the diode increases.
[src:electronics/diode] For instance, a drop of 1 V to 1.5 V is typical at full rated current for silicon power diodes.
[src:electronics/diode] However, a semiconductor diode's exponential current–voltage characteristic is really more gradual than this simple on–off action.
[src:electronics/diode] Since a diode's forward-voltage drop varies only a little with the current, and is more so a function of temperature, this effect can be used as a temperature sensor or as a somewhat imprecise voltage reference.
[src:electronics/diode] A diode's high resistance to current flowing in the reverse direction suddenly drops to a low resistance when the reverse voltage across the diode reaches a value called the breakdown voltage.
[src:electronics/diode] This effect is used to regulate voltage (Zener diodes) or to protect circuits from high voltage surges (avalanche diodes).
[src:electronics/diode] A semiconductor diode's current–voltage characteristic can be tailored by selecting the semiconductor materials and the doping impurities introduced into the materials during manufacture.
[src:electronics/diode] These techniques are used to create special-purpose diodes that perform many different functions.
[src:electronics/diode] For example, to electronically tune radio and TV receivers (varactor diodes), to generate radio-frequency oscillations (tunnel diodes, Gunn diodes, IMPATT diodes), and to produce light (light-emitting diodes).
[src:electronics/diode] Tunnel, Gunn and IMPATT diodes exhibit negative resistance, which is useful in microwave and switching circuits.
[src:electronics/diode] Diodes, both vacuum and semiconductor, can be used as shot-noise generators.
[src:electronics/diode] Thermionic (vacuum-tube) diodes and solid-state (semiconductor) diodes were developed separately, at approximately the same time, in the early 1900s, as radio receiver detectors.
[src:electronics/diode] Until the 1950s, vacuum diodes were used more frequently in radios because the early point-contact semiconductor diodes were less stable.
[src:electronics/diode] In 1873, Frederick Guthrie observed that a grounded, white-hot metal ball brought close to an electroscope would discharge a positively charged electroscope, but not a negatively charged electroscope.
[src:electronics/diode] In 1880, Thomas Edison observed unidirectional current between heated and unheated elements in a bulb, later called Edison effect, and was granted a patent on application of the phenomenon for use in a DC voltmeter.
[src:electronics/diode] About 20 years later, John Ambrose Fleming (scientific adviser to the Marconi Company and former Edison employee) realized that the Edison effect could be used as a radio detector.
[src:electronics/diode] Fleming patented the first true thermionic diode, the Fleming valve, in Britain on 16 November 1904 (followed by U.S. patent 803,684 in November 1905).
[src:electronics/diode] Throughout the vacuum tube era, valve diodes were used in almost all electronics such as radios, televisions, sound systems, and instrumentation.
[src:electronics/diode] They slowly lost market share beginning in the late 1940s due to selenium rectifier technology and then to semiconductor diodes during the 1960s.
[src:electronics/diode] Today they are still used in a few high power applications where their ability to withstand transient voltages and their robustness gives them an advantage over semiconductor devices, and in musical instrument and audiophile applications.
[src:electronics/diode] In 1874, German scientist Karl Ferdinand Braun discovered the "unilateral conduction" across a contact between a metal and a mineral.
[src:electronics/diode] Fitts made a selenium current rectifier c.
[src:electronics/diode] 1886, but his work did not result in any practical devices until the 1930s.
[src:electronics/diode] Indian scientist Jagadish Chandra Bose was the first to use a crystal for detecting radio waves in 1894, and he filed a U.S. patent for detecting radio signals with a galena crystal point-contact semiconductor diode in 1901.
[src:electronics/diode] The crystal detector was developed into a practical device for wireless telegraphy by Greenleaf Whittier Pickard, who invented a silicon crystal detector in 1903 and received a patent for it on 20 November 1906.
[src:electronics/diode] He subsequently founded a company to market "cat’s whisker" crystal radio detectors; probably the first to make and sell commercial silicon semiconductor devices.
[src:electronics/diode] Other experimenters tried a variety of other minerals as detectors (e.g., Henry Dunwoody received a patent using silicon carbide later in 1906 and Wichi Torikata earned a patent in 1908).
[src:electronics/diode] Semiconductor principles were unknown to the developers of these early rectifiers.
[src:electronics/diode] During the 1930s understanding of physics advanced and in the mid-1930s researchers at Bell Telephone Laboratories recognized the potential of the crystal detector for application in microwave technology.
[src:electronics/diode] Researchers at Bell Labs, Western Electric, MIT, Purdue and in the United Kingdom intensively developed point-contact diodes (*crystal rectifiers* or *crystal diodes*) during World War II for application in radar.
[src:electronics/diode] After World War II, AT&T used these in its microwave towers that criss-crossed the United States, and many radar sets use them even in the 21st century.
[src:electronics/diode] In 1946, Sylvania began offering the 1N34 crystal diode.
[src:electronics/diode] During the early 1950s, junction diodes were developed.
[src:electronics/diode] Early asymmetric conduction devices were commonly referred to as rectifiers because their principal use was the conversion of alternating current to direct current.
[src:electronics/diode] In 1919, the year tetrodes were introduced, William Henry Eccles coined the term *diode* from the Greek *di* (δί), meaning "two", and *hodos* (ὁδός), meaning "path".
[src:electronics/diode] The term described a vacuum tube having two electrodes.
[src:electronics/diode] In modern usage the term **diode** refers generally to a two-terminal device that exhibits asymmetric conduction.
[src:electronics/diode] The term **rectifier** is often used more specifically for devices intended for power supply conversion, while *diode* is frequently used for small-signal devices such as detectors or switching elements.
[src:electronics/diode] A similar distinction existed with thermionic devices: small vacuum diodes were commonly used as radio detectors, while larger two-electrode valves designed for power conversion were typically referred to as **rectifier valves** or **rectifiers**.
[src:electronics/diode] A **thermionic diode** is a vacuum tube consisting of a sealed, evacuated glass or metal envelope containing two electrodes: a cathode and a plate.
[src:electronics/diode] The cathode is either *indirectly heated* or *directly heated*.
[src:electronics/diode] If indirect heating is employed, a heater is included in the envelope.
[src:electronics/diode] A directly heated cathode is made of tungsten wire and is heated by a current passed through it from an external voltage source.
[src:electronics/diode] An indirectly heated cathode is heated by infrared radiation from a nearby heater that is formed of Nichrome wire and supplied with current provided by an external voltage source.
[src:electronics/diode] The operating temperature of the cathode causes it to emit electrons into the vacuum by thermionic emission.
[src:electronics/diode] In most receiving tubes the cathode is coated with oxides of alkaline-earth metals, typically barium and strontium oxides, which possess a low work function and therefore emit electrons more readily than bare metal surfaces.
[src:electronics/diode] The plate is not heated and does not normally emit electrons; it serves as the electron-collecting electrode.
[src:electronics/diode] When an alternating voltage is applied between cathode and plate, the diode conducts only when the plate is positive with respect to the cathode.
[src:electronics/diode] In that condition the plate electrostatically attracts electrons emitted by the cathode, and current flows from cathode to plate.
[src:electronics/diode] When the plate is negative with respect to the cathode, it does not emit electrons and the electron stream from the cathode is repelled, so no conduction occurs.
[src:electronics/diode] Under typical operating conditions, the diode current is limited not by emission but by the space charge formed by electrons in transit between cathode and plate.
[src:electronics/diode] In this region the current density follows the Child–Langmuir law, varying approximately as the three-halves power of the plate voltage (Ip ∝ Ep^(3/2)) for fixed electrode spacing.
[src:electronics/diode] Other types of diodes include the mercury vapor diode, the xenon gas diode, the Cold-cathode rectifier, and the magnetron.
[src:electronics/diode] Until about the end of the 1950s diodes that relied on a small diameter metal wire point contact, e. g. tungsten wire, to make contact with a small semiconductor crystal were all called *"crystal detectors"*.
[src:electronics/diode] The contact could be *a non-welded* contact type or *a welded contact* type.
[src:electronics/diode] Non-welded contact construction utilizes the Schottky barrier principle.
[src:electronics/diode] The metal side is the pointed end of a small diameter wire that is in contact with the semiconductor crystal.
[src:electronics/diode] In the welded contact type, a small P region is formed in the otherwise N-type crystal around the metal point during manufacture by momentarily passing a relatively large current through the device.
[src:electronics/diode] With the availibility of vacuum tube diodes for receiver, crystal detectors were mainly used for research and development between 1925 until 1940.
[src:electronics/diode] The need for demodulator for radar applications and test equipment in the microwave bands up to 26 GHz led to the use of Silicon for a crystal detector by Bell Laboratories with production starting in 1942.
[src:electronics/diode] Those crystal detectors had a ceramic case and needed manual adjustment of the point contact during production.
[src:electronics/diode] In February 1946 Silvania Electric introduced a crystal detector that used Germanium instead of Silicon.
[src:electronics/diode] The first models used also a ceramic case, e.g.
[src:electronics/diode] 1N34 while the later model 1N34A had a case made out of glass.
[src:electronics/diode] Unlike the Silicon type crystal detectors the 1N34 diode allowed also useas rectifiers for small currents.
[src:electronics/diode] A p–n junction diode is made of a crystal of semiconductor, usually silicon, but germanium and gallium arsenide are also used.
[src:electronics/diode] Impurities are added to it to create a region on one side that contains negative charge carriers (electrons), called an n-type semiconductor, and a region on the other side that contains positive charge carriers (holes), called a p-type semiconductor.
[src:electronics/diode] When the n-type and p-type materials are attached together, a momentary flow of electrons occurs from the n to the p side resulting in a third region between the two where no charge carriers are present.
[src:electronics/diode] This region is called the depletion region because there are no charge carriers (neither electrons nor holes) in it.
[src:electronics/diode] The diode's terminals are attached to the n-type and p-type regions.
[src:electronics/diode] The boundary between these two regions, called a p–n junction, is where the action of the diode takes place.
[src:electronics/diode] When a sufficiently higher electrical potential is applied to the P side (the anode) than to the N side (the cathode), it allows electrons to flow through the depletion region from the N-type side to the P-type side.
[src:electronics/diode] The junction does not allow the flow of electrons in the opposite direction when the potential is applied in reverse, creating, in a sense, an electrical check valve.
[src:electronics/diode] Another type of junction diode, the Schottky diode, is formed from a metal–semiconductor junction rather than a p–n junction, which reduces capacitance and increases switching speed.
[src:electronics/diode] A semiconductor diode's behavior in a circuit is given by its current–voltage characteristic.
[src:electronics/diode] The shape of the curve is determined by the transport of charge carriers through the so-called *depletion layer* or *depletion region* that exists at the p–n junction between differing semiconductors.
[src:electronics/diode] When a p–n junction is first created, conduction-band (mobile) electrons from the N-doped region diffuse into the P-doped region where there is a large population of holes (vacant places for electrons) with which the electrons "recombine".
[src:electronics/diode] When a mobile electron recombines with a hole, both hole and electron vanish, leaving behind an immobile positively charged donor (dopant) on the N side and negatively charged acceptor (dopant) on the P side.
[src:electronics/diode] The region around the p–n junction becomes depleted of charge carriers and thus behaves as an insulator.
[src:electronics/diode] However, the width of the depletion region (called the depletion width) cannot grow without limit.
[src:electronics/diode] For each electron–hole pair recombination made, a positively charged dopant ion is left behind in the N-doped region, and a negatively charged dopant ion is created in the P-doped region.
[src:electronics/diode] As recombination proceeds and more ions are created, an increasing electric field develops through the depletion zone that acts to slow and then finally stop recombination.
[src:electronics/diode] At this point, there is a "built-in" potential across the depletion zone.
[src:electronics/diode] A diode's current–voltage characteristic can be approximated by four operating regions.
[src:electronics/diode] The *Shockley ideal diode equation* or the *diode law* (named after the bipolar junction transistor co-inventor William Bradford Shockley) models the exponential current–voltage (I–V) relationship of diodes in moderate forward or reverse bias.
[src:electronics/diode] The article Shockley diode equation provides details.
[src:electronics/diode] At forward voltages less than the saturation voltage, the voltage versus current characteristic curve of most diodes is not a straight line.
[src:electronics/diode] The current can be approximated by $I=I_{\text{S}}e^{V_{\text{D}}/(nV_{\text{T}})}$ as explained in the Shockley diode equation article.
[src:electronics/diode] In detector and mixer applications, the current can be estimated by a Taylor's series.
[src:electronics/diode] The odd terms can be omitted because they produce frequency components that are outside the pass band of the mixer or detector.
[src:electronics/diode] Even terms beyond the second derivative usually need not be included because they are small compared to the second order term.
[src:electronics/diode] The desired current component is approximately proportional to the square of the input voltage, so the response is called *square law* in this region.
[src:electronics/diode] Following the end of forwarding conduction in a p–n type diode, a reverse current can flow for a short time.
[src:electronics/diode] The device does not attain its blocking capability until the mobile charge in the junction is depleted.
[src:electronics/diode] The effect can be significant when switching large currents very quickly.
[src:electronics/diode] A certain amount of "reverse recovery time" tr (on the order of tens of nanoseconds to a few microseconds) may be required to remove the reverse recovery charge Qr from the diode.
[src:electronics/diode] During this recovery time, the diode can conduct in the reverse direction.
[src:electronics/diode] This might give rise to a large current in the reverse direction for a short time while the diode is reverse biased.
[src:electronics/diode] The magnitude of such a reverse current is determined by the operating circuit (i.e., the series resistance) and the diode is said to be in the storage-phase.
[src:electronics/diode] In certain real-world cases it is important to consider the losses that are incurred by this non-ideal diode effect.
[src:electronics/diode] However, when the slew rate of the current is not so severe (e.g.
[src:electronics/diode] Line frequency) the effect can be safely ignored.
[src:electronics/diode] For most applications, the effect is also negligible for Schottky diodes.
[src:electronics/diode] The reverse current ceases abruptly when the stored charge is depleted; this abrupt stop is exploited in step recovery diodes for the generation of extremely short pulses.
[src:electronics/diode] Normal (p–n) diodes, which operate as described above, are usually made of doped silicon or germanium.
[src:electronics/diode] Before the development of silicon power rectifier diodes, cuprous oxide and later selenium was used.
[src:electronics/diode] The vast majority of all diodes are the p–n diodes found in CMOS integrated circuits, which include two diodes per pin and many other internal diodes.
[src:electronics/diode] These are diodes that conduct in the reverse direction when the reverse bias voltage exceeds the breakdown voltage.
[src:electronics/diode] This occurs when the reverse electric field applied across the p–n junction causes a wave of ionization, reminiscent of an avalanche, leading to a large current.
[src:electronics/diode] Avalanche diodes are designed to break down at a well-defined reverse voltage without being destroyed.
[src:electronics/diode] The difference between the avalanche diode (which has a reverse breakdown above about 6.2 V) and the Zener is that the channel length of the former exceeds the mean free path of the electrons, resulting in many collisions between them on the way through the channel.
[src:electronics/diode] The only practical difference between the two types is they have temperature coefficients of opposite polarities.
[src:electronics/diode] with the gate shorted to the source, and function like a two-terminal current-limiting analog to the voltage-limiting Zener diode.
[src:electronics/diode] They allow a current through them to rise to a certain value, and then level off at a specific value.
[src:electronics/diode] The 1N21 series and others are used in mixer and detector applications in radar and microwave receivers.
[src:electronics/diode] The 1N34A is another example of a crystal diode.
[src:electronics/diode] when they recombine with the majority carrier on the other side.
[src:electronics/diode] The first LEDs were red and yellow, and higher-frequency diodes have been developed over time.
[src:electronics/diode] coating, or combinations of three LEDs of a different color.
[src:electronics/diode] LEDs can also be used as low-efficiency photodiodes in signal applications.
[src:electronics/diode] Peltier heat pumps may be made from semiconductors, though they do not have any rectifying junctions, they use the differing behavior of charge carriers in N and P-type semiconductor to move heat.
[src:electronics/diode] This is typically an undesired effect, so most semiconductors are packaged in light-blocking material.
[src:electronics/diode] ), so they are packaged in materials that allow light to pass, and are usually PIN (the kind of diode most sensitive to light).
[src:electronics/diode] Multiple photodiodes may be packaged in a single device, either as a linear array or as a two-dimensional array.
[src:electronics/diode] , layer, forming a p-type/intrinsic/n-type structure.
[src:electronics/diode] They are used as radio frequency switches and attenuators.
[src:electronics/diode] , as their central layer can withstand high voltages.
[src:electronics/diode] diodes are constructed from metal to semiconductor contact.
[src:electronics/diode] They have a lower forward voltage drop than p–n junction diodes.
[src:electronics/diode] and prevention of transistor saturation.
[src:electronics/diode] , although their reverse leakage current is in general higher than that of other diodes.
[src:electronics/diode] devices and so do not suffer from minority carrier storage problems that slow down many other diodes—so they have a faster reverse recovery than p–n junction diodes.
[src:electronics/diode] Super barrier diodes are rectifier diodes that incorporate the low forward voltage drop of the Schottky diode with the surge-handling capability and low reverse leakage current of a normal p–n junction diode.
[src:electronics/diode] ) acts as recombination centers, which helps the fast recombination of minority carriers.
[src:electronics/diode] This allows the diode to operate at higher signal frequencies, at the expense of a higher forward voltage drop.
[src:electronics/diode] Gold-doped diodes are faster than other p–n diodes (but not as fast as Schottky diodes).
[src:electronics/diode] They also have less reverse-current leakage than Schottky diodes (but not as good as other p–n diodes).
[src:electronics/diode] relates to the form of the reverse recovery characteristic of these devices.
[src:electronics/diode] and the current is interrupted or reversed, the reverse conduction will cease very abruptly (as in a step waveform).
[src:electronics/diode] SRDs can, therefore, provide very fast voltage transitions by the very sudden disappearance of the charge carriers.
[src:electronics/diode] These devices are specially designed for low-voltage stabilization applications requiring a guaranteed voltage over a wide current range and highly stable over temperature.
[src:electronics/diode] Their p–n junctions have a much larger cross-sectional area than those of a normal diode, allowing them to conduct large currents to ground without sustaining damage.
[src:electronics/diode] allowing amplification of signals and very simple bistable circuits.
[src:electronics/diode] Because of the high carrier concentration, tunnel diodes are very fast, may be used at low (mK) temperatures, high magnetic fields, and in high radiation environments.
[src:electronics/diode] Because of these properties, they are often used in spacecraft.
[src:electronics/diode] ) circuits, allowing tuning circuits, such as those in television receivers, to lock quickly on to the frequency.
[src:electronics/diode] These can be made to conduct in reverse bias (backward), and are correctly termed reverse breakdown diodes.
[src:electronics/diode] , occurs at a precisely defined voltage, allowing the diode to be used as a precision voltage reference.
[src:electronics/diode] The term Zener diodes is colloquially applied to several types of breakdown diodes, but strictly speaking, Zener diodes have a breakdown voltage of below 5 volts, whilst avalanche diodes are used for breakdown voltages above that value.
[src:electronics/diode] In practical voltage reference circuits, Zener and switching diodes are connected in series and opposite directions to balance the temperature coefficient response of the diodes to near-zero.
[src:electronics/diode] Some devices labeled as high-voltage Zener diodes are actually avalanche diodes (see above).
[src:electronics/diode] The symbol used to represent a particular type of diode in a circuit diagram conveys the general electrical function to the reader.
[src:electronics/diode] There are alternative symbols for some types of diodes, though the differences are minor.
[src:electronics/diode] The triangle in the symbols points to the forward direction, i.e. in the direction of conventional current flow.
[src:electronics/diode] The standardized 1N-series numbering *EIA370* system was introduced in the US by EIA/JEDEC (Joint Electron Device Engineering Council) about 1960.
[src:electronics/diode] Most diodes have a 1-prefix designation (e.g., 1N4003).
[src:electronics/diode] Among the most popular in this series were: 1N34A/1N270 (germanium signal), 1N914/1N4148 (silicon signal), 1N400x (silicon 1A power rectifier), and 1N580x (silicon 3A power rectifier).
[src:electronics/diode] The JIS semiconductor designation system has all semiconductor diode designations starting with "1S".
[src:electronics/diode] The European Pro Electron coding system for active components was introduced in 1966 and comprises two letters followed by the part code.
[src:electronics/diode] In optics, an equivalent device for the diode but with laser light would be the optical isolator, also known as an optical diode, that allows light to only pass in one direction.
[src:electronics/diode] It uses a Faraday rotator as the main component.
[src:electronics/diode] The first use for the diode was the demodulation of amplitude modulated (AM) radio broadcasts.
[src:electronics/diode] An AM signal consists of alternating positive and negative peaks of a radio carrier wave, whose amplitude or envelope is proportional to the original audio signal.
[src:electronics/diode] The diode rectifies the AM radio frequency signal, leaving only the positive peaks of the carrier wave.
[src:electronics/diode] The audio is then extracted from the rectified carrier wave using a simple filter and fed into an audio amplifier or transducer, which generates sound waves via audio speaker.
[src:electronics/diode] In microwave and millimeter wave technology, beginning in the 1930s, researchers improved and miniaturized the crystal detector.
[src:electronics/diode] Point contact diodes (*crystal diodes*) and Schottky diodes are used in radar, microwave and millimeter wave detectors.
[src:electronics/diode] Rectifiers are constructed from diodes, where they are used to convert alternating current (AC) electricity into direct current (DC).
[src:electronics/diode] Automotive alternators are a common example, where the diode, which rectifies the AC into DC, provides better performance than the commutator or earlier, dynamo.
[src:electronics/diode] Similarly, diodes are also used in *Cockcroft–Walton voltage multipliers* to convert AC into higher DC voltages.
[src:electronics/diode] Since most electronic circuits can be damaged when the polarity of their power supply inputs are reversed, a series diode is sometimes used to protect against such situations.
[src:electronics/diode] This concept is known by multiple naming variations that mean the same thing: reverse voltage protection, reverse polarity protection, and reverse battery protection.
[src:electronics/diode] Diodes are frequently used to conduct damaging high voltages away from sensitive electronic devices.
[src:electronics/diode] They are usually reverse-biased (non-conducting) under normal circumstances.
[src:electronics/diode] When the voltage rises above the normal range, the diodes become forward-biased (conducting).
[src:electronics/diode] For example, diodes are used in (stepper motor and H-bridge) motor controller and relay circuits to de-energize coils rapidly without the damaging voltage spikes that would otherwise occur.
[src:electronics/diode] (A diode used in such an application is called a flyback diode).
[src:electronics/diode] Many integrated circuits also incorporate diodes on the connection pins to prevent external voltages from damaging their sensitive transistors.
[src:electronics/diode] Specialized diodes are used to protect from over-voltages at higher power (see Diode types above).
[src:electronics/diode] Diode–resistor logic constructs AND and OR logic gates.
[src:electronics/diode] Functional completeness can be achieved by adding an active device to provide inversion (as done with diode–transistor logic).
[src:electronics/diode] In addition to light, mentioned above, semiconductor diodes are sensitive to more energetic radiation.
[src:electronics/diode] In electronics, cosmic rays and other sources of ionizing radiation cause noise pulses and single and multiple bit errors.
[src:electronics/diode] This effect is sometimes exploited by particle detectors to detect radiation.
[src:electronics/diode] A single particle of radiation, with thousands or millions of electron volt, s of energy, generates many charge carrier pairs, as its energy is deposited in the semiconductor material.
[src:electronics/diode] If the depletion layer is large enough to catch the whole shower or to stop a heavy particle, a fairly accurate measurement of the particle's energy can be made, simply by measuring the charge conducted and without the complexity of a magnetic spectrometer, etc.
[src:electronics/diode] These semiconductor radiation detectors need efficient and uniform charge collection and low leakage current.
[src:electronics/diode] They are often cooled by liquid nitrogen.
[src:electronics/diode] For longer-range (about a centimeter) particles, they need a very large depletion depth and large area.
[src:electronics/diode] For short-range particles, they need any contact or un-depleted semiconductor on at least one surface to be very thin.
[src:electronics/diode] The back-bias voltages are near breakdown (around a thousand volts per centimeter).
[src:electronics/diode] Germanium and silicon are common materials.
[src:electronics/diode] Some of these detectors sense position as well as energy.
[src:electronics/diode] They have a finite life, especially when detecting heavy particles, because of radiation damage.
[src:electronics/diode] Silicon and germanium are quite different in their ability to convert gamma rays to electron showers.
[src:electronics/diode] Semiconductor detectors for high-energy particles are used in large numbers.
[src:electronics/diode] Because of energy loss fluctuations, accurate measurement of the energy deposited is of less use.
[src:electronics/diode] A diode can be used as a temperature measuring device, since the forward voltage drop across the diode depends on temperature, as in a silicon bandgap temperature sensor.
[src:electronics/diode] From the Shockley ideal diode equation given above, it might *appear* that the voltage has a *positive* temperature coefficient (at a constant current), but usually the variation of the reverse saturation current term is more significant than the variation in the thermal voltage term.
[src:electronics/diode] Most diodes therefore have a *negative* temperature coefficient, typically −2 mV/°C for silicon diodes.
[src:electronics/diode] The temperature coefficient is approximately constant for temperatures above about 20 kelvin.
[src:electronics/diode] Some graphs are given for 1N400x series, and CY7 cryogenic temperature sensor.
[src:electronics/diode] Diodes will prevent currents in unintended directions.
[src:electronics/diode] To supply power to an electrical circuit during a power failure, the circuit can draw current from a battery.
[src:electronics/diode] An uninterruptible power supply may use diodes in this way to ensure that the current is only drawn from the battery when necessary.
[src:electronics/diode] Likewise, small boats typically have two circuits each with their own battery/batteries: one used for engine starting; one used for domestics.
[src:electronics/diode] Normally, both are charged from a single alternator, and a heavy-duty split-charge diode is used to prevent the higher-charge battery (typically the engine battery) from discharging through the lower-charge battery when the alternator is not running.
[src:electronics/diode] Diodes are also used in electronic musical keyboards.
[src:electronics/diode] To reduce the amount of wiring needed in electronic musical keyboards, these instruments often use keyboard matrix circuits.
[src:electronics/diode] The keyboard controller scans the rows and columns to determine which note the player has pressed.
[src:electronics/diode] The problem with matrix circuits is that, when several notes are pressed at once, the current can flow backward through the circuit and trigger "phantom keys" that cause "ghost" notes to play.
[src:electronics/diode] To avoid triggering unwanted notes, most keyboard matrix circuits have diodes soldered with the switch under each key of the musical keyboard.
[src:electronics/diode] The same principle is also used for the switch matrix in solid-state pinball machines.
[src:electronics/diode] Diodes can be used to limit the positive or negative excursion of a signal to a prescribed voltage.
[src:electronics/diode] A diode clamp circuit can take a periodic alternating current signal that oscillates between positive and negative values, and vertically displace it such that either the positive or the negative peaks occur at a prescribed level.
[src:electronics/diode] The clamper does not restrict the peak-to-peak excursion of the signal, it moves the whole signal up or down so as to place the peaks at the reference level.
[src:electronics/diode] The diode's exponential current–voltage relationship is exploited to evaluate exponentiation and its inverse function the logarithm using analog voltage signals (see Operational amplifier applications §§ Exponential output and Logarithmic output).
[src:electronics/diode] Diodes are usually referred to as *D* for diode on PCBs.
[src:electronics/diode] Sometimes the abbreviation *CR* for *crystal rectifier* is used.
[src:electronics/electric-current] An **electric current** is a flow of charged particles, such as electrons or ions, through an electrical conductor or space.
[src:electronics/electric-current] It is defined as the net rate at which electric charge flows through a surface.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The moving particles are called charge carriers, which may be of several types, depending on the conductor.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In electric circuits, the charge carriers are often electrons moving through a wire.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In semiconductors, the charge carriers can be electrons or holes.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In an electrolyte, the charge carriers are ions, while in plasma- an ionized gas- they are also ions and electrons.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In the International System of Units (SI), electric current is expressed in units of ampere (sometimes called an "amp", symbol A), which is equivalent to one coulomb per second.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The ampere is an SI base unit and electric current is a base quantity in the International System of Quantities (ISQ).
[src:electronics/electric-current] Electric current is also known as **amperage** and is measured using a device called an *ammeter*.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Electric currents create magnetic fields, which are used in motors, generators, inductors, and transformers.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In ordinary conductors, they cause Joule heating, which creates light in incandescent light bulbs.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Time-varying currents emit electromagnetic waves, which are used in telecommunications to broadcast information.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The conventional symbol for current is *I*, which originates from the French phrase *intensité du courant* (current intensity).
[src:electronics/electric-current] Current intensity is often referred to simply as *current*.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The *I* symbol was used by André-Marie Ampère, after whom the unit of electric current is named, in formulating Ampère's force law (1820).
[src:electronics/electric-current] The notation travelled from France to Great Britain, where it became standard, although at least one journal did not change from using *C* to *I* until 1896.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The conventional direction of current, also known as *conventional current*, is arbitrarily defined as the direction in which *positive* charges flow.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In a conductive material, the moving charged particles that constitute the electric current are called charge carriers.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In metals, which make up the wires and other conductors in most electrical circuits, the positively charged atomic nuclei of the atoms are held in a fixed position, and the negatively charged electrons are the charge carriers, free to move about in the metal.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In other materials, notably the semiconductors, the charge carriers can be positive *or* negative, depending on the dopant used.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Positive and negative charge carriers may even be present at the same time, as happens in an electrolyte in an electrochemical cell.
[src:electronics/electric-current] A flow of positive charges gives the same electric current, and has the same effect in a circuit, as an equal flow of negative charges in the opposite direction.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Since current can be the flow of either positive or negative charges, or both, a convention is needed for the direction of current that is independent of the type of charge carriers.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Negatively charged carriers, such as the electrons (the charge carriers in metal wires and many other electronic circuit components), therefore flow in the opposite direction of conventional current flow in an electrical circuit.
[src:electronics/electric-current] A current in a wire or circuit element can flow in either of two directions.
[src:electronics/electric-current] When defining a variable I to represent the current, the direction representing positive current must be specified, usually by an arrow on the circuit schematic diagram.
[src:electronics/electric-current] This is called the *reference direction* of the current I .
[src:electronics/electric-current] When analyzing electrical circuits, the actual direction of current through a specific circuit element is usually unknown until the analysis is completed.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Consequently, the reference directions of currents are often assigned arbitrarily.
[src:electronics/electric-current] When the circuit is solved, a negative value for the current implies the actual direction of current through that circuit element is opposite that of the chosen reference direction.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Ohm's law states that the current through a conductor between two points is directly proportional to the potential difference across the two points.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The constant of proportionality in this relationship is the resistance.
[src:electronics/electric-current] where *I* is the current through the conductor in units of amperes, *V* is the potential difference measured *across* the conductor in units of volts, and *R* is the resistance of the conductor in units of ohms.
[src:electronics/electric-current] More specifically, Ohm's law states that the *R* in this relation is constant, independent of the current.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In alternating current (AC) systems, the movement of electric charge periodically reverses direction.
[src:electronics/electric-current] AC is the form of electric power most commonly delivered to businesses and residences.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The usual waveform of an AC power circuit is a sine wave, though certain applications use alternative waveforms, such as triangular or square waves.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:electronics/electric-current] An important goal in these applications is recovery of information encoded (or *modulated*) onto the AC signal.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In contrast, direct current (DC) refers to a system in which electric charge moves in only one direction (sometimes called unidirectional flow).
[src:electronics/electric-current] Direct current is produced by sources such as batteries, thermocouples, solar cells, and commutator-type electric machines of the dynamo type.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Alternating current can also be converted to direct current through use of a rectifier.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Direct current may flow in a conductor such as a wire, but can also flow through semiconductors, insulators, or even through a vacuum as in electron or ion beams.
[src:electronics/electric-current] An old name for direct current was *galvanic current*.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Natural observable examples of electric current include lightning, static electric discharge, and the solar wind, the source of the polar auroras.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Man-made occurrences of electric current include the flow of conduction electrons in metal wires such as the overhead power lines that deliver electrical energy across long distances and the smaller wires within electrical and electronic equipment.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Eddy currents are electric currents that occur in conductors exposed to changing magnetic fields.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Similarly, electric currents occur, particularly in the surface, of conductors exposed to electromagnetic waves.
[src:electronics/electric-current] When oscillating electric currents flow at the correct voltages within radio antennas, radio waves are generated.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In electronics, other forms of electric current include the flow of electrons through resistors or through the vacuum in a vacuum tube, the flow of ions inside a battery, and the flow of holes within metals and semiconductors.
[src:electronics/electric-current] A biological example of current is the flow of ions in neurons and nerves, responsible for both thought and sensory perception.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Current can be measured using an ammeter.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Electric current can be directly measured with a galvanometer, but this method involves breaking the electrical circuit, which is sometimes inconvenient.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Current can also be measured without breaking the circuit by detecting the magnetic field associated with the current.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Joule heating, also known as *ohmic heating* and *resistive heating*, is the process of power dissipation by which the passage of an electric current through a conductor increases the internal energy of the conductor, converting thermodynamic work into heat.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The phenomenon was first studied by James Prescott Joule in 1841.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Joule immersed a length of wire in a fixed mass of water and measured the temperature rise due to a known current through the wire for a 30 minute period.
[src:electronics/electric-current] By varying the current and the length of the wire he deduced that the heat produced was proportional to the square of the current multiplied by the electrical resistance of the wire.
[src:electronics/electric-current] This relationship is known as Joule's Law.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The SI unit of energy was subsequently named the joule and given the symbol *J*.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The commonly known SI unit of power, the watt (symbol: W), is equivalent to one joule per second.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In an electromagnet a coil of wires behaves like a magnet when an electric current flows through it.
[src:electronics/electric-current] When the current is switched off, the coil loses its magnetism immediately.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Electric current produces a magnetic field.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The magnetic field can be visualized as a pattern of circular field lines surrounding the wire that persists as long as there is current.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Magnetic fields can also be used to make electric currents.
[src:electronics/electric-current] When a changing magnetic field is applied to a conductor, an electromotive force (EMF) is induced, which starts an electric current, when there is a suitable path.
[src:electronics/electric-current] When an electric current flows in a suitably shaped conductor at radio frequencies, radio waves can be generated.
[src:electronics/electric-current] These travel at the speed of light and can cause electric currents in distant conductors.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In metallic solids, electric charge flows by means of electrons, from lower to higher electrical potential.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In other media, any stream of charged objects (ions, for example) may constitute an electric current.
[src:electronics/electric-current] To provide a definition of current independent of the type of charge carriers, *conventional current* is defined as moving in the same direction as the positive charge flow.
[src:electronics/electric-current] So, in metals where the charge carriers (electrons) are negative, conventional current is in the opposite direction to the overall electron movement.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In conductors where the charge carriers are positive, conventional current is in the same direction as the charge carriers.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In a vacuum, a beam of ions or electrons may be formed.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In other conductive materials, the electric current is due to the flow of both positively and negatively charged particles at the same time.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In still others, the current is entirely due to positive charge flow.
[src:electronics/electric-current] For example, the electric currents in electrolytes are flows of positively and negatively charged ions.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In a common lead-acid electrochemical cell, electric currents are composed of positive hydronium ions flowing in one direction, and negative sulfate ions flowing in the other.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Electric currents in sparks or plasma are flows of electrons as well as positive and negative ions.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In ice and in certain solid electrolytes, the electric current is entirely composed of flowing ions.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In a metal, some of the outer electrons in each atom are not bound to the individual molecules as they are in molecular solids, or in full bands as they are in insulating materials, but are free to move within the metal lattice.
[src:electronics/electric-current] These conduction electrons serve as charge carriers that can flow through the conductor as an electric current when an electric field is present.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Metals are particularly conductive because there are many of these free electrons.
[src:electronics/electric-current] With no external electric field applied, these electrons move about randomly due to thermal energy but, on average, there is zero net current within the metal.
[src:electronics/electric-current] At room temperature, the average speed of these random motions is 106 metres per second.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Given a surface through which a metal wire passes, electrons move in both directions across the surface at an equal rate.
[src:electronics/electric-current] As George Gamow wrote in his popular science book, *One, Two, Three...Infinity* (1947), "The metallic substances differ from all other materials by the fact that the outer shells of their atoms are bound rather loosely, and often let one of their electrons go free.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Thus the interior of a metal is filled up with a large number of unattached electrons that travel aimlessly around like a crowd of displaced persons.
[src:electronics/electric-current] When a metal wire is connected across the two terminals of a DC voltage source such as a battery, the source places an electric field across the conductor.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The moment contact is made, the free electrons of the conductor are forced to drift toward the positive terminal under the influence of this field.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The free electrons are therefore the charge carrier in a typical solid conductor.
[src:electronics/electric-current] For a steady flow of charge through a surface, the current *I* (in amperes) can be calculated with the following equation: $I={Q \over t}\,,$ where *Q* is the electric charge transferred through the surface over a time *t*.
[src:electronics/electric-current] If *Q* and *t* are measured in coulombs and seconds respectively, *I* is in amperes.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Electric currents in electrolytes are flows of electrically charged particles (ions).
[src:electronics/electric-current] For example, if an electric field is placed across a solution of Na+ and Cl− (and conditions are right) the sodium ions move towards the negative electrode (cathode), while the chloride ions move towards the positive electrode (anode).
[src:electronics/electric-current] Reactions take place at both electrode surfaces, neutralizing each ion.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Water-ice and certain solid electrolytes called *proton conductors* contain positive hydrogen ions ("protons") that are mobile.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In these materials, electric currents are composed of moving protons, as opposed to the moving electrons in metals.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In certain electrolyte mixtures, brightly coloured ions are the moving electric charges.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The slow progress of the colour makes the current visible.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In air and other ordinary gases below the breakdown field, the dominant source of electrical conduction is via relatively few mobile ions produced by radioactive gases, ultraviolet light, or cosmic rays.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Since the electrical conductivity is low, gases are dielectrics or insulators.
[src:electronics/electric-current] However, once the applied electric field approaches the breakdown value, free electrons become sufficiently accelerated by the electric field to create additional free electrons by colliding, and ionizing, neutral gas atoms or molecules in a process called avalanche breakdown.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The breakdown process forms a plasma that contains enough mobile electrons and positive ions to make it an electrical conductor.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In the process, it forms a light emitting conductive path, such as a spark, arc or lightning.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Plasma is the state of matter where some of the electrons in a gas are stripped or "ionized" from their molecules or atoms.
[src:electronics/electric-current] A plasma can be formed by high temperature, or by application of a high electric or alternating magnetic field as noted above.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Due to their lower mass, the electrons in a plasma accelerate more quickly in response to an electric field than the heavier positive ions, and hence carry the bulk of the current.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The free ions recombine to create new chemical compounds (for example, breaking atmospheric oxygen into single oxygen [O2 → 2O], which then recombine creating ozone [O3]).
[src:electronics/electric-current] Since a "perfect vacuum" contains no charged particles, it normally behaves as a perfect insulator.
[src:electronics/electric-current] However, metal electrode surfaces can cause a region of the vacuum to become conductive by injecting free electrons or ions through either field electron emission or thermionic emission.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Thermionic emission occurs when the thermal energy exceeds the metal's work function, while field electron emission occurs when the electric field at the surface of the metal is high enough to cause tunneling, which results in the ejection of free electrons from the metal into the vacuum.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Externally heated electrodes are often used to generate an electron cloud as in the filament or indirectly heated cathode of vacuum tubes.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Cold electrodes can also spontaneously produce electron clouds via thermionic emission when small incandescent regions (called *cathode spots* or *anode spots*) are formed.
[src:electronics/electric-current] These are incandescent regions of the electrode surface that are created by a localized high current.
[src:electronics/electric-current] These regions may be initiated by field electron emission, but are then sustained by localized thermionic emission once a vacuum arc forms.
[src:electronics/electric-current] These small electron-emitting regions can form quite rapidly, even explosively, on a metal surface subjected to a high electrical field.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Vacuum tubes and krytrons are some of the electronic switching and amplifying devices based on vacuum conductivity.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Superconductivity is a phenomenon of exactly zero electrical resistance and expulsion of magnetic fields occurring in certain materials when cooled below a characteristic critical temperature.
[src:electronics/electric-current] It was discovered by Heike Kamerlingh Onnes on April 8, 1911 in Leiden.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Like ferromagnetism and atomic spectral lines, superconductivity is a quantum mechanical phenomenon.
[src:electronics/electric-current] It is characterized by the Meissner effect, the complete ejection of magnetic field lines from the interior of the superconductor as it transitions into the superconducting state.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The occurrence of the Meissner effect indicates that superconductivity cannot be understood simply as the idealization of *perfect conductivity* in classical physics.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In a semiconductor it is sometimes useful to think of the current as due to the flow of positive "holes" (the mobile positive charge carriers that are places where the semiconductor crystal is missing a valence electron).
[src:electronics/electric-current] This is the case in a p-type semiconductor.
[src:electronics/electric-current] A semiconductor has electrical conductivity intermediate in magnitude between that of a conductor and an insulator.
[src:electronics/electric-current] This means a conductivity roughly in the range of 10−2 to 104 siemens per centimeter (S⋅cm−1).
[src:electronics/electric-current] In the classic crystalline semiconductors, electrons can have energies only within certain bands (i.e. ranges of levels of energy).
[src:electronics/electric-current] Energetically, these bands are located between the energy of the ground state, the state in which electrons are tightly bound to the atomic nuclei of the material, and the free electron energy, the latter describing the energy required for an electron to escape entirely from the material.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The energy bands each correspond to many discrete quantum states of the electrons, and most of the states with low energy (closer to the nucleus) are occupied, up to a particular band called the *valence band*.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The ease of exciting electrons in the semiconductor from the valence band to the conduction band depends on the band gap between the bands.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The size of this energy band gap serves as an arbitrary dividing line (roughly 4 eV) between semiconductors and insulators.
[src:electronics/electric-current] With covalent bonds, an electron moves by hopping to a neighboring bond.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The Pauli exclusion principle requires that the electron be lifted into the higher anti-bonding state of that bond.
[src:electronics/electric-current] For delocalized states, for example in one dimension – that is in a nanowire, for every energy there is a state with electrons flowing in one direction and another state with the electrons flowing in the other.
[src:electronics/electric-current] For a net current to flow, more states for one direction than for the other direction must be occupied.
[src:electronics/electric-current] For this to occur, energy is required, as in the semiconductor the next higher states lie above the band gap.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Often this is stated as: full bands do not contribute to the electrical conductivity.
[src:electronics/electric-current] However, as a semiconductor's temperature rises above absolute zero, there is more energy in the semiconductor to spend on lattice vibration and on exciting electrons into the conduction band.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The current-carrying electrons in the conduction band are known as *free electrons*, though they are often simply called *electrons* if that is clear in context.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Current density is the rate at which charge passes through a chosen unit area.
[src:electronics/electric-current] It is defined as a vector whose magnitude is the current per unit cross-sectional area.
[src:electronics/electric-current] As discussed in Reference direction, the direction is arbitrary.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Conventionally, if the moving charges are positive, then the current density has the same sign as the velocity of the charges.
[src:electronics/electric-current] For negative charges, the sign of the current density is opposite to the velocity of the charges.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In SI units, current density (symbol: j) is expressed in the SI base units of amperes per square metre.
[src:electronics/electric-current] In linear materials such as metals, and under low frequencies, the current density across the conductor surface is uniform.
[src:electronics/electric-current] where I is the current, measured in amperes; V is the potential difference, measured in volts; and R is the resistance, measured in ohms.
[src:electronics/electric-current] For alternating currents, especially at higher frequencies, skin effect causes the current to spread unevenly across the conductor cross-section, with higher density near the surface, thus increasing the apparent resistance.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The mobile charged particles within a conductor move constantly in random directions, like the particles of a gas.
[src:electronics/electric-current] (More accurately, a Fermi gas.) To create a net flow of charge, the particles must also move together with an average drift rate.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Electrons are the charge carriers in most metals and they follow an erratic path, bouncing from atom to atom, but generally drifting in the opposite direction of the electric field.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Typically, electric charges in solids flow slowly.
[src:electronics/electric-current] For example, in a copper wire of cross-section 0.5 mm2, carrying a current of 5 A, the drift velocity of the electrons is on the order of a millimetre per second.
[src:electronics/electric-current] To take a different example, in the near-vacuum inside a cathode ray tube, the electrons travel in near-straight lines at about a tenth of the speed of light.
[src:electronics/electric-current] Any accelerating electric charge, and therefore any changing electric current, gives rise to an electromagnetic wave that propagates at very high speed *outside* the surface of the conductor.
[src:electronics/electric-current] This speed is usually a significant fraction of the speed of light, as can be deduced from Maxwell's equations, and is therefore many times faster than the drift velocity of the electrons.
[src:electronics/electric-current] For example, in AC power lines, the waves of electromagnetic energy propagate through the space between the wires, moving from a source to a distant load, even though the electrons in the wires only move back and forth over a tiny distance.
[src:electronics/electric-current] The ratio of the speed of the surrounding electromagnetic wave to the speed of light in free space is called the velocity factor, and depends on the electromagnetic properties of the conductor and the insulating materials surrounding it, and on their shape and size.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] In electronics, **flip-flops** and **latches** are circuits that have two stable states that can store state information – a bistable multivibrator.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The circuit can be made to change state by signals applied to one or more control inputs and will output its state (often along with its logical complement).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] It is the basic storage element in sequential logic.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops and latches are fundamental building blocks of digital electronics systems used in computers, communications, and many other types of systems.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops and latches are used as data storage elements to store a single *bit* (binary digit) of data; one of its two states represents a *one* and the other represents a *zero*.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Such data storage can be used for storage of *state*, and such a circuit is described as sequential logic in electronics.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] When used in a finite-state machine, the output and next state depend not only on its current input, but also on its current state (and hence, previous inputs).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] It can also be used for counting of pulses, and for synchronizing variably-timed input signals to some reference timing signal.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The term flip-flop has historically referred generically to both level-triggered (asynchronous, transparent, or opaque) and edge-triggered (synchronous, or clocked) circuits that store a single bit of data using gates.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Modern authors reserve the term *flip-flop* exclusively for edge-triggered storage elements and *latches* for level-triggered ones.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The terms *edge-triggered*, and *level-triggered* may be used to avoid ambiguity.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] When a level-triggered latch is enabled, it becomes transparent, but an edge-triggered flip-flop's output only changes on a clock edge (either positive going or negative going).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Different types of flip-flops and latches are available as integrated circuits, usually with multiple elements per chip.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] For example, 74HC75 is a quadruple transparent latch in the 7400 series.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The first electronic latch was invented in 1918 by the British physicists William Eccles and F.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] It was initially called the *Eccles–Jordan trigger circuit* and consisted of two active elements (vacuum tubes).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The design was used in the 1943 British Colossus codebreaking computer and such circuits and their transistorized versions were common in computers even after the introduction of integrated circuits, though latches and flip-flops made from logic gates are also common now.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Early latches were known variously as trigger circuits or multivibrators.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] They differ slightly from some of the definitions given below.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Lindley explains that he heard the story of the JK flip-flop from Eldred Nelson, who is responsible for coining the term while working at Hughes Aircraft.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops in use at Hughes at the time were all of the type that came to be known as J-K.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] In designing a logical system, Nelson assigned letters to flip-flop inputs as follows: #1: A & B, #2: C & D, #3: E & F, #4: G & H, #5: J & K.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Nelson used the notations *j-input* and *k-input* in a patent application filed in 1953.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Transparent or asynchronous latches can be built around a single pair of cross-coupled inverting elements: vacuum tubes, bipolar transistors, field-effect transistors, inverters, and inverting logic gates have all been used in practical circuits.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Clocked flip-flops are specially designed for synchronous systems; such devices ignore their inputs except at the transition of a dedicated clock signal (known as clocking, pulsing, or strobing).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Clocking causes the flip-flop either to change or to retain its output signal based upon the values of the input signals at the transition.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Some flip-flops change output on the rising edge of the clock, others on the falling edge.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Since the elementary amplifying stages are inverting, two stages can be connected in succession (as a cascade) to form the needed non-inverting amplifier.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] In this configuration, each amplifier may be considered as an active inverting feedback network for the other inverting amplifier.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Thus the two stages are connected in a non-inverting loop although the circuit diagram is usually drawn as a symmetric cross-coupled pair (both the drawings are initially introduced in the Eccles–Jordan patent).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops and latches can be divided into common types: SR (set-reset), D (data), T (toggle), and JK (see History section above).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The behavior of a particular type can be described by the characteristic equation that derives the *next* output (*Q*next) in terms of the input signal(s) and/or the current output, Q .
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] When using static gates as building blocks, the most fundamental latch is the asynchronous *set-reset (SR) latch*.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Its two inputs S and R can set the internal state to 1 using the combination S=1 and R=0, and can reset the internal state to 0 using the combination S=0 and R=1.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The SR latch can be constructed from a pair of cross-coupled NOR or NAND logic gates.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The stored bit is present on the output marked Q.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] It is convenient to think of NAND, NOR, AND and OR as controlled operations, where one input is chosen as the control input set and the other bit as the input to be processed depending on the state of the control.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Essentially, they can all be used as switches that either set a specific value or let an input value pass.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The SR NOR latch consists of two parallel NOR gates where the output of each NOR is also fanned out into one input of the other NOR, as shown in the figure.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] We call these output-to-input connections *feedback inputs*, or simply *feedbacks*.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The remaining inputs we will use as *control* inputs as explained above.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Notice that at this point, because everything is symmetric, it does not matter to which inputs the outputs are connected.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] We now break the symmetry by choosing which of the remaining control inputs will be our set and reset and we can call *set NOR* the NOR gate with the set control and *reset NOR* the NOR with the reset control; in the figures the set NOR is the bottom one and the reset NOR is the top one.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The output of the reset NOR will be our stored bit Q, while we will see that the output of the set NOR stores its complement Q.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] To derive the behavior of the SR NOR latch, consider S and R as control inputs and remember that, from the equations above, set and reset NOR with control 1 will fix their outputs to 0, while set and reset NOR with control 0 will act as a NOT gate.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The R = S = 1 combination is called a **restricted combination** or a **forbidden state** because, as both NOR gates then output zeros, it breaks the logical equation Q = **not** Q.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The combination is also inappropriate in circuits where *both* inputs may go low *simultaneously* (i.e. a transition from *restricted* to *hold*).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The output could remain in a metastable state and may eventually lock at either 1 or 0 depending on the propagation time relations between the gates (a race condition).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] To overcome the restricted combination, one can add gates to the inputs that would convert `(S, R) = (1, 1)` to one of the non-restricted combinations.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] This is done in nearly every programmable logic controller.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Alternatively, the restricted combination can be made to *toggle* the output.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The circuit shown below is a basic NAND latch.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The inputs are also generally designated S and R for Set and Reset respectively.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Because the NAND inputs must normally be logic 1 to avoid affecting the latching action, the inputs are considered to be inverted in this circuit (or active low).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The circuit uses the same feedback as SR NOR, just replacing NOR gates with NAND gates, to *remember* and retain its logical state even after the controlling input signals have changed.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Again, recall that a 1-controlled NAND always outputs 0, while a 0-controlled NAND acts as a NOT gate.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] When the S and R inputs are both high, feedback maintains the Q outputs to the previous state.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] When either is zero, they fix their output bits to 0 while to other adapts to the complement.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] From a teaching point of view, SR latches drawn as a pair of cross-coupled components (transistors, gates, tubes, etc.) are often hard to understand for beginners.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] A didactically easier explanation is to draw the latch as a single feedback loop instead of the cross-coupling.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The following is an SR latch built with an AND gate with one inverted input and an OR gate.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Note that the inverter is not needed for the latch functionality, but rather to make both inputs high-active.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Note that the SR AND-OR latch has the benefit that S = 1, R = 1 is well defined.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] In above version of the SR AND-OR latch it gives priority to the R signal over the S signal.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] If priority of S over R is needed, this can be achieved by connecting output Q to the output of the OR gate instead of the output of the AND gate.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The SR AND-OR latch is easier to understand, because both gates can be explained in isolation, again with the control view of AND and OR from above.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] When neither S or R is set, then both the OR gate and the AND gate are in "hold mode", i.e., they let the input through, their output is the input from the feedback loop.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] When input S = 1, then the OR gate outputs 1, regardless of the other input from the feedback loop ("set mode").
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] When input R = 1 then the AND gate outputs 0, regardless of the other input from the feedback loop ("reset mode").
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] And since the AND gate takes the output of the OR gate as input, R has priority over S.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Latches drawn as cross-coupled gates may look less intuitive, as the behavior of one gate appears to be intertwined with the other gate.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The standard NOR or NAND latches could also be re-drawn with the feedback loop, but in their case the feedback loop does not show the same signal value throughout the whole feedback loop.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] However, the SR AND-OR latch has the drawback that it would need an extra inverter, if an inverted Q output is needed.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The JK latch is much less frequently used than the JK flip-flop.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Hence, the JK latch is an SR latch that is made to *toggle* its output (oscillate between 0 and 1) when passed the input combination of 11.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Unlike the JK flip-flop, the 11 input combination for the JK latch is not very useful because there is no clock that directs toggling.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Latches are designed to be *transparent.* That is, input signal changes cause immediate changes in output.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Additional logic can be added to a transparent latch to make it *non-transparent* or *opaque* when another input (an *enable* input) is not asserted.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] A periodic *enable* input signal may be called a *write strobe*.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] When the *enable* input is a clock signal, the latch is said to be **level-sensitive** (to the level of the clock signal), as opposed to **edge-sensitive** like flip-flops below.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] When several *transparent* latches follow each other, if they are all transparent at the same time, signals will propagate through them all.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] However, following a *transparent-high* latch by a *transparent-low* latch (or vice-versa) causes the state and output to only change on clock edges, forming what is called a *master–slave flip-flop*.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] A *gated SR latch* can be made by adding a second level of NAND gates to an *inverted SR latch*.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The extra NAND gates further invert the inputs so a *SR latch* becomes a *gated SR latch* (a *SR latch* would transform into a *gated SR latch* with inverted enable).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Alternatively, a *gated SR latch* (with non-inverting enable) can be made by adding a second level of AND gates to a *SR latch*.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] With E high (*enable* true), the signals can pass through the input gates to the encapsulated latch; all signal combinations except for (0, 0) = *hold* then immediately reproduce on the (Q, Q) output, i.e. the latch is *transparent*.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] With E low (*enable* false) the latch is *closed (opaque)* and remains in the state it was left the last time E was high.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] This latch exploits the fact that, in the two active input combinations (01 and 10) of a gated SR latch, R is the complement of S.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The input NAND stage converts the two D input states (0 and 1) to these two input combinations for the next SR latch by inverting the data input signal.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The low state of the *enable* signal produces the inactive *11* combination.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Thus a gated D-latch may be considered as a *one-input synchronous SR latch*.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] This configuration prevents application of the restricted input combination.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] It is also known as *transparent latch*, *data latch*, or simply *gated latch*.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] It has a *data* input and an *enable* signal (sometimes named *clock*, or *control*).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The word *transparent* comes from the fact that, when the enable input is on, the signal propagates directly through the circuit, from the input D to the output Q.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Gated D-latches are also **level-sensitive** with respect to the level of the clock or enable signal.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Transparent latches are typically used as I/O ports or in asynchronous systems, or in synchronous two-phase systems (synchronous systems that use a two-phase clock), where two latches operating on different clock phases prevent data transparency as in a master–slave flip-flop.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The truth table below shows that when the *e*nable input is 0, the D input has no effect on the output.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The classic gated latch designs have some undesirable characteristics.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] They require dual-rail logic or an inverter.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The input-to-output propagation may take up to three gate delays.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The input-to-output propagation is not constant – some outputs take two gate delays while others take three.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] A successful alternative is the Earle latch.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] It requires only a single data input, and its output takes a constant two gate delays.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] In addition, the two gate levels of the Earle latch can, in some cases, be merged with the last two gate levels of the circuits driving the latch because many common computational circuits have an OR layer followed by an AND layer as their last two levels.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Merging the latch function can implement the latch with no additional gate delays.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The merge is commonly exploited in the design of pipelined computers, and, in fact, was originally developed by John G.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Earle to be used in the IBM System/360 Model 91 for that purpose.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] If the middle NAND gate is omitted, then one gets the **polarity hold latch**, which is commonly used because it demands less logic.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] However, it is susceptible to logic hazard.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] Intentionally skewing the clock signal can avoid the hazard.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The D flip-flop is widely used, and known as a *data* flip-flop.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] The D flip-flop captures the value of the D-input at a definite portion of the clock cycle (such as the rising edge of the clock).
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] That captured value becomes the Q output.
[src:electronics/flip-flop-electronics] At other times, the output Q does not change.
